WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.400
[Amit Varma]: This episode of The Seen and The Unseen is brought to you by Intel.

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:11.600
[Amit Varma]: What is the economy?

00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:14.000
[Amit Varma]: The economy is the lives of real people.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.960
[Amit Varma]: One of my constant laments is that too often we think of the economy as something abstract,

00:00:18.960 --> 00:00:22.480
[Amit Varma]: numbers and graphs and charts and claims and counterclaims,

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:26.160
[Amit Varma]: rather than the story of our lives, which is what it is.

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:29.440
[Amit Varma]: And I find it useful to remind myself of this from time to time.

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:32.320
[Amit Varma]: We tend to be too glib when we talk about the economy.

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:33.680
[Amit Varma]: We should not be glib.

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:36.960
[Amit Varma]: Everything that affects the economy affects our lives.

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:40.480
[Amit Varma]: Every time a number falls or rises, it affects our happiness.

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:44.400
[Amit Varma]: It affects whether some child somewhere will have food to eat tonight.

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:47.360
[Amit Varma]: That is why we must keep talking about the economy.

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:50.480
[Amit Varma]: It has moral importance and humanitarian consequences.

