[Amit Varma]: Thanks, Amit.

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:02.960
[Amit Varma]: So I want to begin by referring to this beautiful book I read a few years back,

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:05.520
[Amit Varma]: and it's a book by an author called Chyna Meevil,

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:08.800
[Amit Varma]: who typically writes science fiction and fantasy and so on,

00:04:08.800 --> 00:04:11.840
[Amit Varma]: and his mother was a big fan of police procedurals.

00:04:11.840 --> 00:04:14.240
[Amit Varma]: So at one point in time, his mother was rather ill,

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:15.600
[Amit Varma]: and eventually she died,

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:18.000
[Amit Varma]: and he wanted to write a book that would satisfy her,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:19.680
[Amit Varma]: which was a police procedural.

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:23.120
[Amit Varma]: But he couldn't let go of his innate love for weirdness

00:04:23.120 --> 00:04:25.120
[Amit Varma]: over what is known as weird fiction.

00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:27.120
[Amit Varma]: So he wrote this book called The City in the City.

00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:29.200
[Amit Varma]: And the plot of The City in the City is that

00:04:29.200 --> 00:04:32.560
[Amit Varma]: there are two cities inhabiting the same space,

00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:34.080
[Amit Varma]: invisible to each other,

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:36.000
[Amit Varma]: The Scene and The Unseen, as it were.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:37.200
[Amit Varma]: And there's a police inspector,

00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:39.600
[Amit Varma]: which is where the police procedural angle comes in.

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:42.560
[Amit Varma]: There's a police inspector who is investigating a murder,

00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:44.720
[Amit Varma]: which he realized took place in the other city,

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:47.520
[Amit Varma]: which is actually occupying exactly the same spaces, right?

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:49.760
[Amit Varma]: It's, and he has to go into the other city

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:50.800
[Amit Varma]: to figure out what happened.

00:04:50.800 --> 00:04:51.840
[Amit Varma]: It's very interesting.

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:54.880
[Amit Varma]: Now, just looking at that as a metaphor for it,

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:56.320
[Amit Varma]: for our current times,

00:04:56.320 --> 00:05:00.800
[Amit Varma]: I think we are living that kind of dual existence

00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:01.760
[Amit Varma]: in a couple of ways.

00:05:02.560 --> 00:05:05.200
[Amit Varma]: One way, of course, is a rather obvious one,

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:09.360
[Amit Varma]: that some aspects of the economy are obviously out of whack

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:11.440
[Amit Varma]: and things are going to hell,

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:13.920
[Amit Varma]: and other aspects like the booming stock market

00:05:13.920 --> 00:05:16.160
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, they look just fantastic.

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:17.360
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time,

00:05:18.080 --> 00:05:22.320
[Amit Varma]: where I find this metaphor most potent is perceptions,

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:24.960
[Amit Varma]: that there are people who really believe

00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:27.360
[Amit Varma]: that India is going to be a superpower,

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:30.480
[Amit Varma]: that everything is in place and so on and so forth.

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:31.840
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time,

00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:34.240
[Amit Varma]: there are people who believe that we are going to hell.

00:05:34.240 --> 00:05:36.640
[Amit Varma]: And I'm much closer to the second category, obviously,

00:05:36.640 --> 00:05:38.480
[Amit Varma]: as you know, as I've, you know,

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:40.400
[Amit Varma]: through all the economy episodes that I've done.

00:05:40.400 --> 00:05:44.080
[Amit Varma]: And before we actually start talking about the economy

00:05:44.080 --> 00:05:46.800
[Amit Varma]: or start discussing what is real and what is not,

00:05:47.360 --> 00:05:49.600
[Amit Varma]: why do you think we are in this situation

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:52.640
[Amit Varma]: where there is, so to say, a city and a city,

00:05:52.640 --> 00:05:54.320
[Amit Varma]: where there are two realities?

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:57.680
[Guest 1]: So, I want to throw in another dimension,

00:05:59.120 --> 00:06:01.440
[Guest 1]: which is that I inhabit two worlds,

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:03.760
[Guest 1]: which you know about.

00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:06.320
[Guest 1]: So, one world is the world of the city

00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:09.840
[Guest 1]: and the world of the stock markets.

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:13.680
[Guest 1]: And we've had more than one occasion

00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:15.040
[Guest 1]: to talk about stock markets,

00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:17.520
[Guest 1]: beginning with your shortest episode,

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:19.760
[Amit Varma]: which was about Rupal Bench.

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:21.760
[Amit Varma]: Which was 11 minutes, my shortest episode.

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:22.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:26.320
[Guest 1]: So, I inhabit that world of which a subset

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:28.240
[Guest 1]: or almost a forerunner of that world

00:06:28.240 --> 00:06:29.760
[Guest 1]: is now the world of startups.

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:32.320
[Guest 1]: But the other world that I inhabit

00:06:32.320 --> 00:06:34.000
[Guest 1]: is the little mountain village

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.520
[Guest 1]: in which I've had a home for almost 30 years now.

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:41.680
[Guest 1]: And I'm not just an occasional visitor

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:43.680
[Guest 1]: and it's not a rich people's enclave.

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:45.440
[Guest 1]: I've been part of that village.

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:49.440
[Guest 1]: And so, I've actually seen now two generations

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:51.360
[Guest 1]: living in that village.

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:55.440
[Guest 1]: So, I'm not a researcher, I'm not a scholar,

00:06:55.440 --> 00:06:56.720
[Guest 1]: I'm not even a reporter,

00:06:57.600 --> 00:06:59.440
[Guest 1]: but I'm a reasonably observant person

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:01.360
[Guest 1]: and I live in their world.

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:04.480
[Guest 1]: You know, I don't meet my city neighbors

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:07.120
[Guest 1]: or I live in the middle of the village.

00:07:08.560 --> 00:07:13.680
[Guest 1]: And these two cities are completely different

00:07:13.680 --> 00:07:18.800
[Guest 1]: and that's my link with a different reality.

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:21.040
[Guest 1]: And it's always given me reality checks.

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:28.720
[Guest 1]: And there are a lot of blinking red lights in that city.

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:29.920
[Guest 1]: Can you elaborate on that?

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:30.420
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:07:32.560 --> 00:07:35.040
[Guest 1]: Most of my observations about that city

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:37.040
[Guest 1]: and perhaps we can talk about them later

00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:39.040
[Guest 1]: are more of the long-term nature.

00:07:39.840 --> 00:07:44.560
[Guest 1]: Because I've seen hopes, aspirations, actions taken

00:07:44.560 --> 00:07:46.720
[Guest 1]: as a result of those hopes and aspirations,

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:49.040
[Guest 1]: particularly with regard to education

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:51.040
[Guest 1]: and where they've ended up.

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:57.920
[Guest 1]: But this year, I've seen a lot more

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:02.000
[Guest 1]: and this year I spent six months in the village.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.840
[Guest 1]: I just came back 10 days ago

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:08.480
[Guest 1]: and I saw things that I've never seen before.

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:12.640
[Guest 1]: The first time ever in 30 years,

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:14.720
[Guest 1]: walking on the main road,

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:17.520
[Guest 1]: I had somebody stop and ask me

00:08:17.520 --> 00:08:18.800
[Guest 1]: whether I could give him work.

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:21.920
[Guest 1]: It has never happened to me.

00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:27.040
[Guest 1]: I felt lousy because I had four staff.

00:08:28.240 --> 00:08:29.120
[Guest 1]: I was overstaffed.

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:30.800
[Guest 1]: I wasn't letting anybody go.

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:31.840
[Guest 1]: I had to say no.

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:36.240
[Guest 2]: I'm curious, was this person working in the city?

00:08:36.240 --> 00:08:39.840
[Guest 2]: I mean, in urban areas before and just lost his job?

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:40.340
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

00:08:41.360 --> 00:08:42.480
[Guest 1]: And I was coming to that,

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:46.480
[Guest 1]: which is that in a radius of four kilometers,

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:48.800
[Guest 1]: now four kilometers can mean very different things

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:50.240
[Guest 1]: in different parts of the world.

00:08:50.240 --> 00:08:53.200
[Guest 1]: Four kilometers radius in South Delhi,

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:55.360
[Guest 1]: where we are now, would probably be a million people.

00:08:56.720 --> 00:08:59.200
[Guest 1]: Four kilometers radius in that mountain village

00:08:59.200 --> 00:09:00.960
[Guest 1]: is probably about 400 people.

00:09:00.960 --> 00:09:01.920
[Guest 1]: I'm not exaggerating.

00:09:03.120 --> 00:09:09.120
[Guest 1]: I know at least six men between 20 and 40

00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:13.600
[Guest 1]: who came back from the city because there was no work

00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:15.600
[Guest 1]: and they're making do.

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:18.640
[Guest 1]: What I liked was the can-do spirit.

00:09:19.760 --> 00:09:22.720
[Guest 1]: Nobody's just sitting at home and be mourning their loss.

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:24.240
[Guest 1]: They're trying to do something.

00:09:25.200 --> 00:09:26.880
[Guest 1]: They're willing to work with their hands.

00:09:27.600 --> 00:09:29.200
[Guest 1]: Two young men are running a dhaba.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.560
[Guest 1]: I asked them how the dhaba is doing.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.880
[Guest 1]: And so at first it was, oh, it's good.

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:42.080
[Guest 1]: But that dhaba became my turnaround point

00:09:42.080 --> 00:09:43.920
[Guest 1]: when I was coming back from the city.

00:09:43.920 --> 00:09:47.520
[Guest 1]: Turnaround point, when I ran from the house down the road,

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:48.960
[Guest 1]: the dhaba was my turnaround point.

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:52.640
[Guest 1]: And I would stop there and ask them for a glass of water.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:54.960
[Guest 1]: And I got to chatting with them and they said,

00:09:55.600 --> 00:09:59.600
[Guest 1]: look, we are making one fifth of what we made in the city.

00:10:00.720 --> 00:10:04.160
[Guest 1]: But we know that there's nothing in the city.

00:10:04.160 --> 00:10:05.200
[Guest 1]: And so we're making do.

00:10:09.120 --> 00:10:12.640
[Guest 1]: The second, which is not directly related to the economy,

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:17.840
[Guest 1]: but I think it has very profound repercussions down the line,

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:24.160
[Guest 1]: is that kids did not go to school for a year and a half or two.

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:27.280
[Guest 1]: And they've forgotten everything.

00:10:29.600 --> 00:10:33.520
[Guest 1]: Whether you're talking about six or seven-year-olds

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:36.000
[Guest 1]: or you're talking about kids in the 10th or 11th standard.

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:41.680
[Guest 1]: Kids were passed from the 9th into the 10th

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:43.200
[Guest 1]: and now they're going into the 11th.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
[Guest 1]: Having studied for three months in the 9th,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.720
[Guest 1]: not studied at all through the 10th and now entering the 11th.

00:10:52.240 --> 00:10:55.440
[Guest 1]: Two months after the academic year would have started.

00:10:56.080 --> 00:10:58.240
[Guest 1]: As it is in that village, Amit,

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:03.440
[Guest 1]: the pass percentage typically at the board level is 26%.

00:11:04.480 --> 00:11:05.680
[Guest 1]: What is it going to be now?

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:10.960
[Amit Varma]: We'll come back to talking about the immediate aftermath of COVID

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:13.040
[Amit Varma]: and a lot of this also relates to that.

00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:16.720
[Amit Varma]: And previous guests have also given me some insight into that.

00:11:16.720 --> 00:11:20.320
[Amit Varma]: But just to continue with that question of the city in the city,

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:23.680
[Amit Varma]: part of this is really a question,

00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:26.160
[Amit Varma]: not just a division in the economy,

00:11:26.160 --> 00:11:28.960
[Amit Varma]: say in a place like Satholi or the economy in this,

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:31.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, in one sphere of the economy,

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:33.520
[Amit Varma]: like the stock market and another sphere,

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:35.200
[Amit Varma]: but also in perceptions.

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:38.560
[Amit Varma]: And you've, Pooja, been a journalist yourself,

00:11:38.560 --> 00:11:40.160
[Amit Varma]: you've been active on social media

00:11:40.160 --> 00:11:42.720
[Amit Varma]: and what you must have noticed with great dismay,

00:11:42.720 --> 00:11:44.480
[Amit Varma]: as I have over the last few years,

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:47.120
[Amit Varma]: is that it's become such a polarized space

00:11:47.120 --> 00:11:48.960
[Amit Varma]: where there is no space for nuance,

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:53.200
[Amit Varma]: like no longer is a policy evaluated on the basis of

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:55.280
[Amit Varma]: how good or bad the policy might be.

00:11:55.280 --> 00:11:57.920
[Amit Varma]: And all policies will contain a mix of good and bad,

00:11:57.920 --> 00:11:59.920
[Amit Varma]: except for demonetization, which was all bad.

00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:02.960
[Amit Varma]: What we see today is that people choose their tribe.

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:04.320
[Amit Varma]: They go by the tribe.

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:06.480
[Amit Varma]: Everything one tribe, their tribe does is good.

00:12:06.480 --> 00:12:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Everything the other tribe does is bad.

00:12:08.480 --> 00:12:10.880
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, it is a natural division,

00:12:10.880 --> 00:12:13.200
[Amit Varma]: where if you say anything bad about the economy,

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.920
[Amit Varma]: you will have defensive screaming and shouting and trolling.

00:12:17.920 --> 00:12:20.000
[Amit Varma]: And if you say anything good about the economy

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.400
[Amit Varma]: or anything good that the government might do,

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:25.040
[Amit Varma]: you will have a similar reaction from the other side.

00:12:25.040 --> 00:12:27.840
[Amit Varma]: And you've, of course, been at the receiving end of this

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:30.080
[Amit Varma]: multiple times from all sides,

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:32.480
[Amit Varma]: because you write it as you see it,

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:34.960
[Amit Varma]: and the world is complex and the economy is complex.

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:37.440
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about this increasing trend.

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:41.600
[Amit Varma]: Like, am I overperceiving it because I spend so much time on Twitter?

00:12:42.800 --> 00:12:45.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, or what's your kind of sense?

00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:48.560
[Amit Varma]: Does it become more difficult for you as a journalist

00:12:48.560 --> 00:12:51.760
[Amit Varma]: to do financial journalism, to write it as you see it?

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:54.560
[Amit Varma]: Because there is no appetite for that kind of complexity anymore.

00:12:55.840 --> 00:12:59.920
[Guest 2]: Actually, Amit, what you're saying about social media is absolutely right.

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:03.120
[Guest 2]: People are no longer interested on the social media

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:05.200
[Guest 2]: in what's going on in the economy.

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:09.440
[Guest 2]: They're more interested in who are we going to say is right

00:13:09.440 --> 00:13:10.800
[Guest 2]: and who we are going to say is wrong.

00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:12.800
[Guest 2]: And that is almost always, you know,

00:13:12.800 --> 00:13:16.080
[Guest 2]: which country they belong to or which ideology they subscribe to,

00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:17.120
[Guest 2]: whose supporter they are.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.440
[Guest 2]: And so most people who used to earlier come to social media,

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:24.560
[Guest 2]: Twitter, especially, you know, to read new things,

00:13:24.560 --> 00:13:26.720
[Guest 2]: to figure out new things to read about,

00:13:26.720 --> 00:13:29.440
[Guest 2]: for conversations to learn about new things,

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:31.520
[Guest 2]: are withdrawing because it's just politics.

00:13:31.520 --> 00:13:33.520
[Guest 2]: It's no longer about the economy.

00:13:33.520 --> 00:13:36.720
[Guest 2]: Is this becoming a problem to do financial journalism?

00:13:36.720 --> 00:13:37.840
[Guest 2]: Actually, no.

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:39.760
[Guest 2]: I think I get trolled for this.

00:13:39.760 --> 00:13:45.200
[Guest 2]: But, you know, I have now been a financial journalist

00:13:46.240 --> 00:13:49.360
[Guest 2]: during the tenures of multiple governments.

00:13:49.920 --> 00:13:55.440
[Guest 2]: I don't think this government is more adversarial to me

00:13:56.240 --> 00:13:57.840
[Guest 2]: than the previous government was.

00:13:58.800 --> 00:14:01.920
[Guest 2]: Yes, there is a new rule that the

00:14:01.920 --> 00:14:05.120
[Guest 2]: incumbent finance minister introduced

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:06.800
[Guest 2]: soon after she became the finance minister,

00:14:06.800 --> 00:14:09.520
[Guest 2]: where she doesn't allow us to enter

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:11.040
[Guest 2]: North Block, the finance ministry,

00:14:11.040 --> 00:14:14.640
[Guest 2]: and which is strange because, you know,

00:14:14.640 --> 00:14:17.440
[Guest 2]: when a journalist enters North Block

00:14:17.440 --> 00:14:19.040
[Guest 2]: and meets senior bureaucrats,

00:14:19.040 --> 00:14:20.880
[Guest 2]: you're not going to go meet junior bureaucrats.

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:22.720
[Guest 2]: When you meet senior bureaucrats,

00:14:22.720 --> 00:14:24.560
[Guest 2]: sometimes in the corridor for two seconds,

00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:27.280
[Guest 2]: you know, almost always, what are you getting?

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:29.280
[Guest 2]: You're getting their version, you know,

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:32.400
[Guest 2]: their response to something that is being talked about.

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:34.880
[Guest 2]: And you're helping them put out their version.

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:38.080
[Guest 2]: And, you know, that sort of generates a debate

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:41.440
[Guest 2]: or, you know, creates an input into the public discourse.

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:45.120
[Guest 2]: It is almost always helping them, you know.

00:14:45.120 --> 00:14:48.080
[Guest 2]: So I never understood why she introduced this new rule.

00:14:48.080 --> 00:14:50.640
[Guest 2]: In whatever little one-on-one interactions

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:51.280
[Guest 2]: I've had with her,

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:54.160
[Guest 2]: I found her contrary to her public image,

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:56.800
[Guest 2]: quite well informed, quite articulate,

00:14:56.800 --> 00:14:57.920
[Guest 2]: quite willing to listen

00:14:57.920 --> 00:15:00.560
[Guest 2]: and very well read as well.

00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:04.560
[Guest 2]: So I don't understand why she doesn't want journalists

00:15:04.560 --> 00:15:06.560
[Guest 2]: to do the job that, you know,

00:15:06.560 --> 00:15:08.640
[Guest 2]: finance ministry beach reporters were doing earlier.

00:15:09.280 --> 00:15:11.840
[Guest 2]: And whatever my personal experience is,

00:15:11.840 --> 00:15:14.000
[Guest 2]: I've been very critical of this government

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:15.680
[Guest 2]: as I was of the government before this.

00:15:16.240 --> 00:15:19.600
[Guest 2]: I have not found anybody holding that against me.

00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:22.080
[Guest 2]: I have not found access being reduced.

00:15:22.800 --> 00:15:24.480
[Guest 2]: So maybe this is my experience.

00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:26.560
[Guest 2]: It is not the same experience with other journalists.

00:15:26.560 --> 00:15:28.560
[Guest 2]: But, you know, it's not made my job

00:15:28.560 --> 00:15:31.360
[Guest 2]: as a financial journalist difficult.

00:15:31.360 --> 00:15:33.920
[Guest 2]: And I also want to say that I've had

00:15:33.920 --> 00:15:36.720
[Guest 2]: very, very few instances of editors

00:15:37.760 --> 00:15:39.920
[Guest 2]: refusing to publish a submission

00:15:39.920 --> 00:15:45.120
[Guest 2]: which is too critical or, you know, not in line,

00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:46.880
[Guest 2]: maybe not, maybe praising something

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:49.200
[Guest 2]: that they don't want praised, either ways.

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:52.800
[Guest 2]: So that is there a bit, at least in Delhi,

00:15:52.800 --> 00:15:55.520
[Guest 2]: I find editors are sensitive.

00:15:55.520 --> 00:15:58.320
[Guest 2]: Sometimes pieces, submissions are not published,

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:02.320
[Guest 2]: but it's not as bad as the, you know,

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:04.880
[Guest 2]: the chat on Twitter suggests.

00:16:04.880 --> 00:16:09.520
[Guest 2]: That said, on television, it's really bad.

00:16:10.240 --> 00:16:12.560
[Guest 2]: And even in print media, you know,

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:16.080
[Guest 2]: so when I was in day-to-day reporting,

00:16:16.960 --> 00:16:18.960
[Guest 2]: we would almost always say that

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:20.880
[Guest 2]: the government today said this,

00:16:20.880 --> 00:16:23.840
[Guest 2]: but the, you know, but the actual data is this, right?

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:24.960
[Guest 2]: So we would say that.

00:16:24.960 --> 00:16:27.760
[Guest 2]: We would say Finance Minister P Chidambaram today said,

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:30.160
[Guest 2]: made a claim that this is what it is in the press conference.

00:16:30.160 --> 00:16:31.760
[Guest 2]: But, you know, the facts are this.

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:34.720
[Guest 2]: It doesn't happen like that these days.

00:16:35.360 --> 00:16:37.600
[Guest 2]: Nobody says the government today said this.

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:40.000
[Guest 2]: It is, this is what it is, you know,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.760
[Guest 2]: as if what the government is saying

00:16:41.760 --> 00:16:43.760
[Guest 2]: is the ultimate truth, you know,

00:16:43.760 --> 00:16:46.080
[Guest 2]: and no facts need to be presented to show that,

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:48.000
[Guest 2]: well, you know, they're not giving you the full truth.

00:16:48.640 --> 00:16:51.040
[Guest 2]: Those kind of fact checks, I would call them,

00:16:51.040 --> 00:16:52.720
[Guest 2]: that were happening at a day-to-day basis

00:16:52.720 --> 00:16:55.040
[Guest 2]: on daily reporting have just sort of gone off.

00:16:55.040 --> 00:16:57.680
[Guest 1]: But I see some newspapers resorting to

00:16:58.720 --> 00:17:00.080
[Guest 1]: slightly cleverer tactics.

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:01.840
[Guest 1]: So they'll print a piece,

00:17:01.840 --> 00:17:05.200
[Guest 1]: which is clearly a government press release,

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:07.840
[Guest 1]: and they'll print something side-by-side,

00:17:07.840 --> 00:17:08.960
[Guest 1]: which presents the facts.

00:17:08.960 --> 00:17:09.440
[Unknown]: Yes.

00:17:09.440 --> 00:17:12.080
[Unknown]: So it's a slightly cleverer way of doing it.

00:17:12.080 --> 00:17:13.520
[Guest 1]: They're not buried in the same piece,

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:16.400
[Guest 1]: but they're there for the intelligent viewer to realize that

00:17:17.280 --> 00:17:18.560
[Guest 1]: we are forced to say this

00:17:18.560 --> 00:17:20.400
[Guest 1]: because this is what the Finance Minister,

00:17:20.400 --> 00:17:21.840
[Guest 1]: for example, has said,

00:17:21.840 --> 00:17:24.480
[Guest 1]: but this is our version of the reality.

00:17:24.480 --> 00:17:26.720
[Guest 1]: But not every newspaper is going to do that.

00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:28.480
[Guest 2]: And the other thing, sorry, Amit,

00:17:28.480 --> 00:17:30.080
[Guest 2]: the other thing I want to say that, you know,

00:17:30.080 --> 00:17:32.960
[Guest 2]: which I'm not a fan of is that,

00:17:32.960 --> 00:17:35.760
[Guest 2]: you know, you have ministers and politicians

00:17:35.760 --> 00:17:38.880
[Guest 2]: and bureaucrats, chief economic advisors, etc,

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:41.040
[Guest 2]: all the time on the news pages, right?

00:17:41.040 --> 00:17:42.880
[Guest 2]: They get so much column space.

00:17:43.680 --> 00:17:46.320
[Guest 2]: Why do they get now so much column space

00:17:46.320 --> 00:17:47.600
[Guest 2]: on the opinion pages?

00:17:47.600 --> 00:17:50.320
[Guest 2]: Everything that they're saying on news is often,

00:17:50.320 --> 00:17:53.360
[Guest 2]: I mean, more than often their opinion,

00:17:53.360 --> 00:17:55.520
[Guest 2]: you know, why do newspapers,

00:17:55.520 --> 00:17:56.480
[Guest 2]: I mean, the Prime Minister,

00:17:57.360 --> 00:18:00.080
[Guest 2]: you know, the President, the Vice President,

00:18:00.080 --> 00:18:03.360
[Guest 2]: why are the opinion pages dominated by these individuals

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:06.560
[Guest 2]: who in any case get to say what they have to say?

00:18:06.560 --> 00:18:08.560
[Guest 2]: Why is this space not being given,

00:18:08.560 --> 00:18:12.480
[Guest 2]: you know, to other more neutral, more researched?

00:18:12.480 --> 00:18:15.280
[Guest 2]: And, you know, we want to listen to a variety of opinions.

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:17.600
[Guest 2]: These people already get a lot of space in play.

00:18:17.600 --> 00:18:21.760
[Amit Varma]: So, I have a slightly weird sounding question,

00:18:21.760 --> 00:18:24.720
[Amit Varma]: which is, given the changes that you're talking about

00:18:24.720 --> 00:18:25.680
[Amit Varma]: that back in the day,

00:18:25.680 --> 00:18:27.120
[Amit Varma]: and like, first of all, you know,

00:18:27.120 --> 00:18:29.200
[Amit Varma]: I, Mohit, I completely buy that.

00:18:29.200 --> 00:18:30.800
[Amit Varma]: I've seen some newspapers do this as well,

00:18:30.800 --> 00:18:32.400
[Unknown]: side by side, they'll print something like,

00:18:32.400 --> 00:18:35.440
[Amit Varma]: much like the Telegraph of Calcutta famously will print,

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:36.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, quotes in that manner.

00:18:36.800 --> 00:18:37.680
[Guest 1]: They'll put a quote.

00:18:37.680 --> 00:18:38.960
[Guest 1]: Detective Herald as well.

00:18:38.960 --> 00:18:39.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah.

00:18:39.840 --> 00:18:41.360
[Amit Varma]: So, which is very clever.

00:18:41.360 --> 00:18:43.360
[Amit Varma]: But my point there is you shouldn't have to do that.

00:18:43.360 --> 00:18:44.160
[Amit Varma]: Of course not.

00:18:44.160 --> 00:18:47.280
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, which takes me to the question

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:49.520
[Amit Varma]: that since people have to do that,

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:53.040
[Amit Varma]: since, you know, if the government says it is raining,

00:18:53.040 --> 00:18:55.200
[Amit Varma]: you're not allowed to go to the window and say,

00:18:55.200 --> 00:18:56.320
[Amit Varma]: see whether it's raining or not.

00:18:56.320 --> 00:18:57.680
[Amit Varma]: You have to report what the government said.

00:18:58.880 --> 00:19:00.000
[Amit Varma]: Have the journalists changed?

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:01.680
[Amit Varma]: Or have the journalists changed?

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:05.440
[Amit Varma]: In the sense that have a different set of people

00:19:05.440 --> 00:19:08.800
[Amit Varma]: who are more pliable, taken over, you know,

00:19:09.680 --> 00:19:11.200
[Amit Varma]: economic reporting and all that,

00:19:11.200 --> 00:19:13.520
[Amit Varma]: or have the same set of people

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:15.680
[Amit Varma]: learn to moderate themselves?

00:19:15.680 --> 00:19:18.240
[Guest 2]: You know, I think that is true.

00:19:18.240 --> 00:19:22.400
[Guest 2]: Also, I see a rise in the middle career,

00:19:22.400 --> 00:19:25.600
[Guest 2]: mid-career, mid-level levels of the hierarchies

00:19:25.600 --> 00:19:28.400
[Guest 2]: in newspapers of very mediocre people,

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:29.840
[Guest 2]: people who are not specialists.

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:33.120
[Guest 2]: This is exactly what happens in television news channels,

00:19:33.120 --> 00:19:35.280
[Guest 2]: where the anchors, the star anchors,

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:36.560
[Guest 2]: who especially the right wing,

00:19:37.520 --> 00:19:40.800
[Guest 2]: you know, government supporters are always after,

00:19:42.080 --> 00:19:43.840
[Guest 2]: you know, one day they're an expert on health,

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:46.720
[Guest 2]: the next day they're anchoring a programme on the economy,

00:19:46.720 --> 00:19:47.920
[Guest 2]: the third day it's on Bollywood,

00:19:47.920 --> 00:19:49.840
[Guest 2]: then it's crime, then it's politics.

00:19:49.840 --> 00:19:52.800
[Guest 2]: They don't want to give space to, you know,

00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:57.600
[Guest 2]: specialist journalists who have institutional memory

00:19:57.600 --> 00:20:00.160
[Guest 2]: and experience of reporting from the ground.

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:03.760
[Guest 2]: On these, you know, these are very specialised topics.

00:20:03.760 --> 00:20:06.080
[Guest 2]: These star journalists want to interview,

00:20:06.080 --> 00:20:08.560
[Guest 2]: if an international economist is visiting India,

00:20:08.560 --> 00:20:10.480
[Guest 2]: they want to interview the finance minister.

00:20:10.480 --> 00:20:13.680
[Guest 2]: They don't want to let their economic editors

00:20:13.680 --> 00:20:14.400
[Guest 2]: do it.

00:20:14.400 --> 00:20:16.880
[Guest 2]: That reduces the quality of the journalism

00:20:16.880 --> 00:20:18.320
[Guest 2]: being done on TV channels.

00:20:19.040 --> 00:20:21.920
[Guest 2]: And it's sort of really crashed now.

00:20:21.920 --> 00:20:24.400
[Guest 2]: And I see a similar thing happening in newspapers.

00:20:25.120 --> 00:20:26.240
[Guest 2]: We don't see, you know,

00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:30.960
[Guest 2]: if you look at the economic reporting

00:20:30.960 --> 00:20:33.680
[Guest 2]: that is happening in newspapers,

00:20:33.680 --> 00:20:35.280
[Guest 2]: if it doesn't have depth,

00:20:35.280 --> 00:20:38.160
[Guest 2]: much of it is because journalists have become pliable,

00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:39.760
[Guest 2]: because they are risk averse,

00:20:39.760 --> 00:20:41.200
[Guest 2]: because they don't want to lose their job.

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:42.880
[Guest 2]: They don't know, you know, what's going to happen

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:45.680
[Guest 2]: because it is true that what people write

00:20:45.680 --> 00:20:47.120
[Guest 2]: is very closely monitored.

00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:49.040
[Unknown]: It was not monitored in this way earlier.

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:50.800
[Guest 2]: I won't be surprised.

00:20:50.800 --> 00:20:52.960
[Guest 2]: In fact, I've heard of people,

00:20:53.680 --> 00:20:57.040
[Guest 2]: editors of papers getting calls, complaints.

00:20:58.480 --> 00:21:01.520
[Guest 2]: Some people got transferred out of Delhi,

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:03.200
[Guest 2]: women journalists.

00:21:03.920 --> 00:21:06.640
[Guest 2]: So, you know, everybody's just being careful.

00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:08.560
[Guest 2]: But the thing is that, you know,

00:21:08.560 --> 00:21:11.440
[Guest 2]: you have to keep testing the boundary, you know.

00:21:11.440 --> 00:21:12.880
[Guest 2]: But if you're a journalist, you know,

00:21:12.880 --> 00:21:14.880
[Guest 2]: who doesn't know how they're going to pay

00:21:14.880 --> 00:21:16.080
[Guest 2]: their next EMI and all,

00:21:16.080 --> 00:21:17.840
[Guest 2]: you're not going to test the boundary.

00:21:17.840 --> 00:21:19.920
[Guest 2]: So that phenomenon is sort of playing out.

00:21:20.640 --> 00:21:24.960
[Guest 2]: I think this is more for the leadership in the media,

00:21:25.760 --> 00:21:29.040
[Guest 2]: for them, you know, to sort of create that safe space

00:21:29.040 --> 00:21:32.400
[Guest 2]: for mid-level journalists to be able to do a better job.

00:21:32.960 --> 00:21:37.280
[Guest 2]: I am less willing to, you know,

00:21:37.280 --> 00:21:40.880
[Guest 2]: sort of look at the mid-level and the junior journalists

00:21:40.880 --> 00:21:42.960
[Guest 2]: and say, well, they're at fault.

00:21:42.960 --> 00:21:45.280
[Guest 2]: They'll do, they take cues from their bosses.

00:21:45.280 --> 00:21:47.040
[Guest 2]: So they'll do what, you know, they're allowed to do.

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:50.400
[Amit Varma]: So an interesting phrase I learned recently,

00:21:50.400 --> 00:21:54.000
[Amit Varma]: which kind of expresses so much that is true about the world

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:56.000
[Amit Varma]: and interesting phenomenon rather is called

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:57.360
[Amit Varma]: the Gelman amnesia effect.

00:21:57.360 --> 00:21:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Have you heard of it?

00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:00.880
[Amit Varma]: So it's a phrase coined by Michael Crichton.

00:22:00.880 --> 00:22:03.920
[Amit Varma]: His close friend was a physicist Murray Gelman.

00:22:03.920 --> 00:22:06.480
[Amit Varma]: And Gelman once made the observation

00:22:06.480 --> 00:22:08.240
[Amit Varma]: that when I read something in the newspaper

00:22:08.240 --> 00:22:10.400
[Amit Varma]: about a field that I know very well,

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:11.680
[Amit Varma]: I know that it is nonsense.

00:22:12.320 --> 00:22:14.480
[Amit Varma]: But the rest of what is in the newspaper

00:22:14.480 --> 00:22:16.160
[Amit Varma]: about fields I don't know well,

00:22:16.160 --> 00:22:18.000
[Amit Varma]: I will take it as a gospel truth.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:19.280
[Amit Varma]: And he called this, you know,

00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:23.040
[Guest 2]: This is absolutely right.

00:22:23.040 --> 00:22:25.120
[Guest 2]: I feel this about The Economist magazine often.

00:22:26.160 --> 00:22:27.760
[Amit Varma]: A lot of the things that we read about

00:22:27.760 --> 00:22:31.840
[Guest 1]: what they write on India are quite off the mark, you know.

00:22:32.480 --> 00:22:34.960
[Guest 1]: So in general, I think it's true, you know,

00:22:34.960 --> 00:22:38.960
[Guest 1]: because even taking into account what Pooja said,

00:22:38.960 --> 00:22:41.120
[Guest 1]: which is a more relative phenomenon,

00:22:41.120 --> 00:22:43.360
[Guest 1]: which is of people not being able

00:22:43.360 --> 00:22:45.360
[Guest 1]: to develop their speciality.

00:22:45.360 --> 00:22:48.400
[Guest 1]: But even otherwise, I think that to some extent,

00:22:48.400 --> 00:22:50.080
[Guest 1]: it's a natural phenomenon.

00:22:50.080 --> 00:22:52.720
[Guest 1]: Because if I'm a practitioner,

00:22:53.360 --> 00:22:57.920
[Guest 1]: there's no way that a journalist is going to know about

00:22:57.920 --> 00:23:00.080
[Guest 1]: as much about that field as I am.

00:23:00.880 --> 00:23:02.000
[Guest 1]: So that's bound to happen.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.080
[Guest 1]: The extent to which it happens

00:23:04.080 --> 00:23:07.840
[Guest 1]: is a matter of observation and judgment.

00:23:07.840 --> 00:23:09.280
[Guest 1]: But it's bound to happen.

00:23:09.280 --> 00:23:10.640
[Guest 1]: You know, I run a company,

00:23:11.360 --> 00:23:14.640
[Guest 1]: an interviewer comes and interviews me about the company.

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:16.160
[Guest 1]: When I read it, I say,

00:23:16.720 --> 00:23:18.400
[Guest 1]: it's got a few facts wrong, you know.

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:20.640
[Guest 1]: He can't know as much.

00:23:21.840 --> 00:23:24.400
[Guest 1]: But I think there's a broader point there,

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:27.120
[Guest 1]: while I'm not denying anything of what you're saying.

00:23:27.120 --> 00:23:29.840
[Guest 1]: The fear effect, the boundaries being reduced,

00:23:29.840 --> 00:23:31.680
[Guest 1]: self-censorship, all of those I see.

00:23:33.440 --> 00:23:35.920
[Guest 1]: But I think there's another factor at work,

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:39.360
[Guest 1]: which is that all my adult life,

00:23:40.720 --> 00:23:44.000
[Guest 1]: Indian journalism has been very, very under-researched,

00:23:45.120 --> 00:23:47.040
[Guest 1]: under-budgeted, under-researched.

00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:51.280
[Guest 1]: So, you know, you compare it to an economist

00:23:51.280 --> 00:23:53.200
[Guest 1]: or a Harvard Business Review or whatever,

00:23:53.200 --> 00:23:55.040
[Guest 1]: they're going to assign a writer

00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:58.160
[Guest 1]: for a month to do something like this.

00:23:58.160 --> 00:23:59.760
[Guest 1]: Here you do it in two or three days.

00:23:59.760 --> 00:24:01.440
[Guest 1]: So there's that phenomenon at work as well.

00:24:01.440 --> 00:24:02.880
[Amit Varma]: Let's say that, let's say that.

00:24:02.880 --> 00:24:05.280
[Amit Varma]: Often, you know, there are places I've heard of people

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:07.040
[Amit Varma]: under pressure to put out two stories a day.

00:24:07.680 --> 00:24:08.960
[Amit Varma]: How can you do anything?

00:24:10.240 --> 00:24:12.480
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the reason I remember the Gelman-Amnesia effect

00:24:12.480 --> 00:24:15.520
[Amit Varma]: is because of what you said about mediocrity kind of rising.

00:24:15.520 --> 00:24:18.880
[Amit Varma]: And of course, it is true that while every specialist

00:24:18.880 --> 00:24:20.480
[Amit Varma]: will feel that the journalism in the field,

00:24:20.480 --> 00:24:23.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, cannot possibly be entirely accurate

00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:24.480
[Amit Varma]: and get all the nuances.

00:24:24.480 --> 00:24:26.400
[Amit Varma]: But what you see in journalism in the West,

00:24:26.400 --> 00:24:29.840
[Amit Varma]: and even there, it's true that it's a lot of the time,

00:24:29.840 --> 00:24:32.160
[Amit Varma]: it's quite shoddy and all that.

00:24:32.160 --> 00:24:34.000
[Amit Varma]: But what you kind of see in the West is that

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:36.320
[Amit Varma]: there is at least that effort, that time given,

00:24:36.320 --> 00:24:38.880
[Amit Varma]: like you mentioned, you have much more time to do stories.

00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:40.480
[Amit Varma]: But over here, it's just rubbish.

00:24:40.480 --> 00:24:41.600
[Amit Varma]: There's just no understanding.

00:24:41.600 --> 00:24:43.200
[Amit Varma]: You go from beat to beat to beat.

00:24:43.200 --> 00:24:45.200
[Amit Varma]: Now, this is OK for a lot of stuff.

00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:48.160
[Amit Varma]: But I just feel that it is not OK for economics.

00:24:48.960 --> 00:24:51.360
[Guest 2]: Or, you know, foreign policy, defense.

00:24:51.360 --> 00:24:52.640
[Amit Varma]: Or foreign policy, defense.

00:24:52.640 --> 00:24:55.280
[Amit Varma]: You just cannot have Monday morning quarterbacks,

00:24:55.280 --> 00:24:58.400
[Amit Varma]: as it were, coming in and kind of giving gyan to this.

00:24:58.400 --> 00:25:00.320
[Amit Varma]: And the sense I got from what you're saying

00:25:00.320 --> 00:25:01.920
[Amit Varma]: is that there is more of that happening.

00:25:01.920 --> 00:25:03.680
[Guest 2]: There is, I mean, you know,

00:25:03.680 --> 00:25:07.360
[Guest 2]: for somebody who's never studied GDP in college,

00:25:07.360 --> 00:25:09.600
[Guest 2]: to begin to interpret the GDP data,

00:25:09.600 --> 00:25:13.920
[Guest 2]: when, you know, economists who have their entire careers

00:25:13.920 --> 00:25:15.920
[Guest 2]: worked on this subject are telling us that,

00:25:15.920 --> 00:25:18.240
[Guest 2]: you know, I'm finding, I mean, Arvind Subramanian,

00:25:18.240 --> 00:25:19.760
[Guest 2]: for instance, wrote in the economic survey

00:25:19.760 --> 00:25:21.920
[Guest 2]: that I'm puzzled by the GDP estimate.

00:25:21.920 --> 00:25:24.240
[Guest 2]: But we had political journalists holding forth.

00:25:24.240 --> 00:25:26.720
[Guest 1]: And, you know, so, I mean.

00:25:26.720 --> 00:25:29.520
[Guest 1]: I am very puzzled by the GDP, you know.

00:25:29.520 --> 00:25:30.880
[Guest 1]: I won't say I'm an economist,

00:25:30.880 --> 00:25:33.920
[Guest 1]: but I have studied and I'm very puzzled by the GDP.

00:25:33.920 --> 00:25:34.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, quick plug.

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:37.120
[Amit Varma]: I had a great episode on GDP with Rajeshwari Sengupta.

00:25:37.120 --> 00:25:38.480
[Guest 1]: I remember that one, yeah.

00:25:38.480 --> 00:25:41.200
[Amit Varma]: The other thing that is happening in the journalistic space

00:25:41.200 --> 00:25:44.320
[Amit Varma]: is that it is very muddied now

00:25:44.320 --> 00:25:47.520
[Amit Varma]: by this mixture of opinion and news, number one,

00:25:47.520 --> 00:25:49.200
[Amit Varma]: with all these Monday morning quarterbacks

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:50.400
[Amit Varma]: coming up with their estimates

00:25:50.400 --> 00:25:52.480
[Amit Varma]: without knowing what the hell they're talking about.

00:25:52.480 --> 00:25:55.440
[Amit Varma]: And also this need to drive narratives,

00:25:55.440 --> 00:25:59.520
[Amit Varma]: like that's kind of led to an infusion of bullshit.

00:25:59.520 --> 00:26:02.400
[Amit Varma]: And by bullshit, I don't mean that in a pejorative sense.

00:26:02.400 --> 00:26:03.680
[Guest 1]: I think it's fine.

00:26:03.680 --> 00:26:04.640
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I agree.

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:08.320
[Amit Varma]: Let me tell you the sense I mean it in.

00:26:08.320 --> 00:26:10.640
[Amit Varma]: Harry Frankfurt wrote this great book called On Bullshit,

00:26:11.280 --> 00:26:14.880
[Amit Varma]: where his theory was that bullshit is different from lies.

00:26:14.880 --> 00:26:17.440
[Amit Varma]: Lies are when you know that something is false,

00:26:17.440 --> 00:26:19.760
[Amit Varma]: you know the truth and you choose to lie.

00:26:19.760 --> 00:26:21.440
[Amit Varma]: Bullshit is when you don't know anything.

00:26:21.440 --> 00:26:23.600
[Amit Varma]: You're just saying whatever the hell comes into your mind.

00:26:23.600 --> 00:26:25.600
[Guest 1]: But there's a third very important factor

00:26:25.600 --> 00:26:29.120
[Guest 1]: which ties up with the need to be able to bullshit,

00:26:30.240 --> 00:26:38.240
[Guest 1]: which is that we have seen such a massive reduction

00:26:39.280 --> 00:26:41.840
[Guest 1]: in data production of the last seven years.

00:26:43.120 --> 00:26:46.400
[Guest 1]: Data on the economy is not available.

00:26:46.400 --> 00:26:51.040
[Guest 1]: India used to have a really sophisticated statistical system.

00:26:52.080 --> 00:26:55.120
[Guest 1]: It was way ahead of where we were as a country.

00:26:55.120 --> 00:26:58.160
[Guest 1]: As a country in our GDP, etc, etc.

00:26:58.160 --> 00:27:03.360
[Guest 1]: There has been systematic destruction of that whole ecosystem.

00:27:04.480 --> 00:27:07.040
[Guest 1]: To the extent that you've had people at the top

00:27:07.680 --> 00:27:10.240
[Guest 1]: of the statistical system resigning.

00:27:12.080 --> 00:27:13.360
[Guest 2]: Let me double click on this.

00:27:13.360 --> 00:27:13.840
[Unknown]: Yeah, please.

00:27:13.840 --> 00:27:14.720
[Guest 2]: Can I add to that?

00:27:14.720 --> 00:27:15.200
[Guest 2]: Please, please.

00:27:15.200 --> 00:27:17.280
[Guest 2]: So, we were talking about GDP.

00:27:18.240 --> 00:27:20.800
[Guest 2]: So, the base is getting into slightly technical thing.

00:27:20.800 --> 00:27:23.920
[Guest 2]: The base is revised every five years, right?

00:27:23.920 --> 00:27:26.400
[Guest 2]: I sort of stay away from most conversations

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:28.880
[Guest 2]: in the economy these days because the GDP estimates,

00:27:28.880 --> 00:27:31.920
[Guest 2]: you know, the base year has not been revised now for 10 years.

00:27:32.640 --> 00:27:34.240
[Guest 2]: And last time when they revised it,

00:27:34.240 --> 00:27:36.640
[Guest 2]: there was such a big noise because they had to,

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:39.600
[Guest 2]: they had to sort of revise downwards the previous estimates.

00:27:39.600 --> 00:27:41.520
[Guest 2]: And there is a technical reason why that happens.

00:27:41.520 --> 00:27:44.800
[Guest 2]: Because when you, you know, how they arrive at GDP estimates,

00:27:44.800 --> 00:27:47.440
[Guest 2]: as both of you know, is that it's a combination

00:27:47.440 --> 00:27:50.080
[Guest 2]: of a few surveys that are done in the base year.

00:27:50.080 --> 00:27:52.880
[Guest 2]: And then, you know, a few surveys that are done year to year.

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:54.000
[Guest 2]: Year to year.

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:56.400
[Guest 2]: And they keep extrapolating on the basis of the base year,

00:27:56.400 --> 00:27:58.640
[Guest 2]: what new information comes in, new data comes in,

00:27:58.640 --> 00:27:59.520
[Guest 2]: new surveys come in.

00:28:00.080 --> 00:28:04.880
[Guest 2]: When they extrapolate on the basis of the base year for 10 years,

00:28:04.880 --> 00:28:08.000
[Guest 2]: they invariably end up inflating estimates.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:11.200
[Guest 2]: You know, there are technical papers that people have written about this.

00:28:11.760 --> 00:28:13.520
[Guest 2]: My fear is that, you know,

00:28:13.520 --> 00:28:17.120
[Guest 2]: the estimates that we are going to see now are not very accurate.

00:28:17.920 --> 00:28:21.600
[Guest 1]: In fact, since you're talking about the technical part of it,

00:28:21.600 --> 00:28:24.480
[Guest 1]: the other technical part of it is that when you rebase,

00:28:24.480 --> 00:28:27.600
[Guest 1]: you also present data for the previous years.

00:28:27.600 --> 00:28:29.120
[Guest 1]: They didn't do that for two years.

00:28:29.680 --> 00:28:30.560
[Unknown]: There's a big question mark.

00:28:30.560 --> 00:28:32.160
[Unknown]: There's a big question mark around it.

00:28:32.160 --> 00:28:33.600
[Guest 1]: And when they finally did it,

00:28:34.560 --> 00:28:39.280
[Guest 1]: it was to reduce the growth from the previous regime

00:28:39.280 --> 00:28:41.600
[Guest 1]: and increase the growth from the current regime.

00:28:41.600 --> 00:28:43.040
[Guest 1]: It's bound to be suspect.

00:28:44.080 --> 00:28:45.600
[Guest 1]: You're bound to suspect it.

00:28:45.600 --> 00:28:48.000
[Guest 1]: But that's the gross data, right?

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:49.680
[Guest 1]: But you talk about other data.

00:28:49.680 --> 00:28:51.680
[Guest 1]: You talk about consumption data.

00:28:51.680 --> 00:28:53.040
[Guest 1]: You talk about employment data.

00:28:53.040 --> 00:28:54.800
[Guest 1]: The consumption data was ready.

00:28:55.360 --> 00:28:57.040
[Guest 1]: It was released.

00:28:58.160 --> 00:28:59.440
[Guest 1]: And then it was pulled back.

00:28:59.440 --> 00:29:00.240
[Guest 1]: Inconvenient.

00:29:01.120 --> 00:29:04.000
[Guest 1]: And they said that it has been pulled back

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:06.240
[Guest 1]: because it has not been approved by the ministry.

00:29:06.880 --> 00:29:09.120
[Guest 1]: But it has never been approved by the ministry before

00:29:09.120 --> 00:29:11.360
[Guest 1]: because it was released by the Department of Statistics.

00:29:12.240 --> 00:29:12.880
[Guest 1]: When was this?

00:29:12.880 --> 00:29:13.840
[Guest 1]: About three years ago.

00:29:13.840 --> 00:29:14.880
[Guest 1]: I forget the exact date.

00:29:14.880 --> 00:29:16.000
[Guest 2]: Just before the elections.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:16.480
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:29:16.480 --> 00:29:17.520
[Guest 2]: Yeah, so roughly about three years ago.

00:29:17.520 --> 00:29:18.560
[Guest 2]: It didn't cut a very good picture.

00:29:18.560 --> 00:29:22.320
[Guest 1]: It was pulled back because the data that showed

00:29:22.320 --> 00:29:23.840
[Guest 1]: was really, really inconvenient.

00:29:24.880 --> 00:29:28.320
[Guest 1]: And the statistician who was in charge of it,

00:29:28.320 --> 00:29:30.480
[Guest 1]: the chief statistician at that point resigned.

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:34.240
[Guest 1]: And then along with him, the next guy also resigned.

00:29:35.200 --> 00:29:36.800
[Guest 1]: So you've completely destroyed.

00:29:38.160 --> 00:29:41.840
[Guest 1]: Then what happened is when it comes to employment data,

00:29:41.840 --> 00:29:42.640
[Guest 1]: same problems.

00:29:43.600 --> 00:29:47.040
[Guest 1]: As a result, everybody started relying on private data,

00:29:47.040 --> 00:29:48.800
[Guest 1]: which is the data released by the CMI,

00:29:49.440 --> 00:29:51.280
[Guest 1]: the Center for Monitoring the Indian Economy.

00:29:52.160 --> 00:29:54.480
[Guest 1]: Now, when that data is inconvenient,

00:29:54.480 --> 00:29:55.920
[Guest 1]: you say, oh, we can't rely on that data

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:56.800
[Guest 1]: because it's private data.

00:29:58.000 --> 00:29:59.360
[Guest 1]: So see how this fits in.

00:30:00.400 --> 00:30:02.560
[Guest 1]: So there's no data, no official data.

00:30:04.080 --> 00:30:06.560
[Guest 1]: If the private data is inconvenient,

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:08.320
[Guest 1]: you say we can't rely on private data.

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:11.760
[Guest 1]: This lays the road open for any narrative

00:30:11.760 --> 00:30:14.000
[Guest 1]: because now it's your opinion versus my opinion

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:14.960
[Guest 1]: because there is no data.

00:30:14.960 --> 00:30:18.400
[Guest 2]: And what that tells us is that all that matters is opinion.

00:30:18.400 --> 00:30:18.960
[Guest 2]: Exactly.

00:30:18.960 --> 00:30:20.640
[Guest 2]: I mean, policy needs data.

00:30:20.640 --> 00:30:22.960
[Guest 2]: So my bigger worry is that, you know,

00:30:23.600 --> 00:30:27.200
[Guest 2]: why do we seek better data?

00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:29.360
[Guest 2]: Why are the policymakers not,

00:30:29.360 --> 00:30:30.960
[Guest 2]: they should be the ones, you know,

00:30:30.960 --> 00:30:33.680
[Guest 2]: louder on this saying we need the data,

00:30:33.680 --> 00:30:36.960
[Guest 2]: we need better data because we are, you know, flying blind.

00:30:36.960 --> 00:30:38.560
[Guest 1]: So Pooja, I have a question for you,

00:30:38.560 --> 00:30:44.640
[Guest 1]: which is, who is the economic policymaker today?

00:30:44.640 --> 00:30:46.640
[Guest 2]: Who is an economic policymaker today?

00:30:46.640 --> 00:30:49.920
[Guest 2]: Oh, the Prime Minister's office.

00:30:49.920 --> 00:30:52.880
[Guest 1]: Right, and who in the Prime Minister's office?

00:30:53.440 --> 00:30:54.480
[Guest 1]: I wish I knew.

00:30:54.480 --> 00:30:54.980
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:30:55.680 --> 00:30:56.640
[Guest 1]: This is the problem.

00:30:58.960 --> 00:31:01.440
[Guest 1]: You have somebody who's reporting on the economy.

00:31:03.120 --> 00:31:04.800
[Guest 1]: Pooja, you have someone like me

00:31:04.800 --> 00:31:06.560
[Guest 1]: who's been observing the economy,

00:31:06.560 --> 00:31:08.800
[Guest 1]: observing the economy, sometimes casually,

00:31:08.800 --> 00:31:10.720
[Guest 1]: sometimes in depth for 50 years.

00:31:11.360 --> 00:31:11.860
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:31:12.560 --> 00:31:15.680
[Guest 1]: I joined an undergrad in economics

00:31:16.480 --> 00:31:18.320
[Guest 1]: when I was 16 years old.

00:31:18.320 --> 00:31:19.920
[Guest 1]: I'm now going to be 66.

00:31:19.920 --> 00:31:21.440
[Guest 1]: 50 years I've been observing the economy.

00:31:22.560 --> 00:31:23.920
[Guest 1]: We're both sitting in Delhi

00:31:25.440 --> 00:31:27.120
[Guest 1]: and we're saying we don't know

00:31:27.920 --> 00:31:30.880
[Guest 1]: who crafts economic policy for the government of India.

00:31:30.880 --> 00:31:37.120
[Guest 1]: What can be a bigger indictment of what is happening in this country?

00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:45.200
[Guest 1]: When is the last time that you heard an economic policy statement

00:31:46.080 --> 00:31:50.320
[Guest 1]: from anybody who wore a title on their badge?

00:31:52.160 --> 00:31:54.560
[Guest 2]: We used to hear of turf wars earlier

00:31:54.560 --> 00:31:57.280
[Guest 2]: between ministers, between bureaucrats,

00:31:57.280 --> 00:31:58.480
[Guest 2]: between the Prime Minister's office

00:31:58.480 --> 00:31:59.680
[Guest 2]: and the Finance Minister's office,

00:31:59.680 --> 00:32:01.680
[Guest 2]: depending on the politics,

00:32:01.680 --> 00:32:03.600
[Guest 2]: or in different governments.

00:32:03.600 --> 00:32:05.280
[Guest 2]: We don't hear any of that today

00:32:05.280 --> 00:32:11.200
[Guest 2]: because, well, policymaking is not being done in ministry.

00:32:11.200 --> 00:32:12.240
[Amit Varma]: Fantastic meta point.

00:32:12.240 --> 00:32:14.960
[Amit Varma]: And I was earlier going to double click on the data question

00:32:14.960 --> 00:32:17.760
[Amit Varma]: and ask for specifics on, you know,

00:32:17.760 --> 00:32:19.360
[Amit Varma]: what kind of data is no longer coming

00:32:19.360 --> 00:32:20.720
[Amit Varma]: and why is it no longer coming?

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:21.680
[Amit Varma]: The why is kind of clear.

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:24.160
[Amit Varma]: But instead, I'm going to sort of combine these two themes

00:32:24.720 --> 00:32:28.000
[Amit Varma]: and sort of explore this,

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:31.280
[Amit Varma]: that, and this is again sounding like the data and the data,

00:32:31.280 --> 00:32:34.480
[Amit Varma]: that there's a very big way in which society has changed

00:32:34.480 --> 00:32:37.200
[Amit Varma]: in the last 30 years, beyond economics and beyond India,

00:32:37.200 --> 00:32:39.040
[Amit Varma]: which is that 30 years ago,

00:32:39.040 --> 00:32:42.320
[Amit Varma]: you could say that there was a broad consensus on the truth.

00:32:42.320 --> 00:32:45.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, you had a few mainstream newspaper, mainstream media,

00:32:45.440 --> 00:32:49.120
[Amit Varma]: there was a broad consensus on basic aspects of the truth,

00:32:49.120 --> 00:32:52.080
[Amit Varma]: that the sun rises in the east and blah, blah, blah, all of those things.

00:32:52.880 --> 00:32:56.240
[Amit Varma]: Today, what has happened is one media has become extremely fragmented

00:32:56.240 --> 00:32:58.160
[Amit Varma]: and in many ways, that's a good thing.

00:32:58.160 --> 00:33:01.840
[Amit Varma]: It's empowered individual creators, it's democratized the space,

00:33:01.840 --> 00:33:04.560
[Amit Varma]: you can have more debate, more space for dissent.

00:33:04.560 --> 00:33:06.400
[Amit Varma]: But what it's also done is that

00:33:06.400 --> 00:33:10.560
[Amit Varma]: because the way we consume information is so fragmented,

00:33:10.560 --> 00:33:12.320
[Amit Varma]: and because of the different ways

00:33:12.320 --> 00:33:16.080
[Amit Varma]: in which social media has increased tribalism,

00:33:16.080 --> 00:33:19.280
[Amit Varma]: what it often means is that there is no consensus on the truth.

00:33:19.280 --> 00:33:21.440
[Amit Varma]: You can believe whatever the hell you want.

00:33:21.440 --> 00:33:25.520
[Amit Varma]: And this then kind of leads me to one,

00:33:25.520 --> 00:33:27.920
[Amit Varma]: one, then I don't know why anyone would suppress data,

00:33:27.920 --> 00:33:30.000
[Amit Varma]: because what difference does it make anyway?

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:32.320
[Amit Varma]: But from where you are, one, there is this tendency

00:33:32.320 --> 00:33:35.440
[Amit Varma]: that the reality doesn't matter, the narrative matters,

00:33:35.440 --> 00:33:38.320
[Amit Varma]: which in politics, I think is clearly true,

00:33:38.320 --> 00:33:41.120
[Amit Varma]: up to a point where I think there's,

00:33:41.120 --> 00:33:43.040
[Amit Varma]: I am hopeful that there's got to be a tipping point

00:33:43.040 --> 00:33:45.120
[Amit Varma]: when the reality has to start to matter.

00:33:45.120 --> 00:33:46.960
[Amit Varma]: We didn't see that with demonetization,

00:33:46.960 --> 00:33:48.320
[Amit Varma]: and we haven't seen it with COVID.

00:33:48.960 --> 00:33:52.640
[Amit Varma]: But as a journalist, as someone who follows the economy,

00:33:52.640 --> 00:33:56.160
[Amit Varma]: when you think of data, that fine, all these sources of data

00:33:56.160 --> 00:34:00.400
[Amit Varma]: are no longer reliable, but these sources were a few sources,

00:34:00.400 --> 00:34:02.320
[Amit Varma]: some of them were government sources.

00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:05.280
[Amit Varma]: If you have to think creatively on your feet and say,

00:34:05.280 --> 00:34:07.520
[Amit Varma]: look, I want to get to the truth anyway,

00:34:07.520 --> 00:34:10.160
[Amit Varma]: what are the kind of proxies that you use?

00:34:10.160 --> 00:34:12.800
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there is, of course, the anecdotal stuff

00:34:12.800 --> 00:34:14.880
[Amit Varma]: that you bring in that, you know, I was in Sitholi,

00:34:14.880 --> 00:34:17.280
[Amit Varma]: and this is what I see around me, and that's anecdotal.

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:19.760
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, if you want to make sense of the world,

00:34:19.760 --> 00:34:23.760
[Amit Varma]: you cannot believe anybody because everybody seems to have an agenda.

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:25.600
[Amit Varma]: They're coming from all these places.

00:34:25.600 --> 00:34:28.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, we've discussed the state of the media.

00:34:28.640 --> 00:34:31.760
[Amit Varma]: What is then your approach to even get at the truth?

00:34:31.760 --> 00:34:35.360
[Amit Varma]: And within that, is there a warning to yourself

00:34:35.360 --> 00:34:36.560
[Amit Varma]: to fight your own biases?

00:34:37.200 --> 00:34:40.480
[Guest 2]: Yes, Amit, you know, 30 years ago, what you say,

00:34:40.480 --> 00:34:43.600
[Guest 2]: if there was a consensus, probably because

00:34:43.600 --> 00:34:46.400
[Guest 2]: there was very clearly a very dominating side, right?

00:34:46.400 --> 00:34:51.040
[Guest 2]: Only the people who got space and whose voices were heard,

00:34:51.040 --> 00:34:54.640
[Guest 2]: they got to determine what the truth, so to say, was.

00:34:54.640 --> 00:34:56.000
[Guest 2]: We don't know if that was the truth.

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:57.920
[Guest 2]: I mean, you know, it's very difficult for us,

00:34:57.920 --> 00:35:01.680
[Guest 2]: for me to, you know, because we've not heard the other side, right?

00:35:01.680 --> 00:35:04.240
[Guest 2]: What you're saying, what is happening now is

00:35:04.240 --> 00:35:07.280
[Guest 2]: with this democratization of opinion,

00:35:07.280 --> 00:35:08.640
[Guest 2]: people stating their opinions,

00:35:08.640 --> 00:35:10.320
[Guest 2]: we are getting to hear more and more people

00:35:10.320 --> 00:35:11.920
[Guest 2]: who were voiceless earlier.

00:35:11.920 --> 00:35:16.240
[Guest 2]: So, I'm not so, I don't have this view that earlier,

00:35:16.240 --> 00:35:18.640
[Guest 2]: that if we have a view of what the truth was,

00:35:18.640 --> 00:35:19.680
[Guest 2]: I mean, whose truth?

00:35:19.680 --> 00:35:21.440
[Guest 2]: You know, that question always is asked.

00:35:21.440 --> 00:35:24.320
[Amit Varma]: No, I agree that it's, I actually think it's a net positive.

00:35:24.320 --> 00:35:25.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:35:25.120 --> 00:35:26.480
[Guest 2]: Usually a net positive.

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:29.200
[Unknown]: But there is then the negative side of it that

00:35:29.200 --> 00:35:31.200
[Amit Varma]: the truth almost begins to count for nothing.

00:35:31.200 --> 00:35:33.680
[Guest 1]: It's what you want to believe that determines what you believe.

00:35:33.680 --> 00:35:35.840
[Guest 1]: But as far as data is concerned, you know,

00:35:35.840 --> 00:35:38.960
[Guest 1]: specifically this point of data,

00:35:38.960 --> 00:35:44.480
[Guest 1]: like I said, I grew up at a time where you trusted government data, number one.

00:35:45.200 --> 00:35:46.000
[Guest 1]: And I still do.

00:35:46.800 --> 00:35:48.320
[Guest 1]: I still trust government data.

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:51.040
[Guest 1]: And two, the data was really good.

00:35:52.080 --> 00:35:54.000
[Guest 1]: It was released to a timetable, etc.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:56.240
[Guest 1]: Give us some specifics, like what kind of data would we get,

00:35:56.240 --> 00:35:57.360
[Amit Varma]: which we don't get today?

00:35:57.360 --> 00:35:58.800
[Amit Varma]: And why don't we get it today?

00:35:58.800 --> 00:35:59.360
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

00:35:59.360 --> 00:36:04.720
[Guest 1]: So, like I said, we are not getting consumption data, you know.

00:36:04.720 --> 00:36:06.800
[Guest 1]: What is the average household consumption?

00:36:06.800 --> 00:36:09.200
[Guest 1]: You know, what is the average household consuming?

00:36:09.200 --> 00:36:11.360
[Amit Varma]: That was, that was stopped.

00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:13.920
[Amit Varma]: Okay, give me a sense of who collects this and how they collect it.

00:36:13.920 --> 00:36:15.520
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I just want to kind of really get.

00:36:16.800 --> 00:36:20.960
[Guest 1]: I'm not very good at that, but mostly by the Ministry of Statistics and

00:36:22.320 --> 00:36:23.360
[Guest 1]: MOSPI as it's called.

00:36:23.920 --> 00:36:27.600
[Guest 1]: Then you have the NSO, the National Statistical Organization,

00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:30.080
[Guest 1]: which has these periodic surveys, etc, etc.

00:36:30.880 --> 00:36:32.000
[Guest 1]: They don't cook up data.

00:36:32.720 --> 00:36:35.120
[Guest 1]: The problem is that data releases have stopped.

00:36:35.120 --> 00:36:40.400
[Guest 1]: Employment data from the government, consumption data, all of these have stopped.

00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:43.920
[Guest 1]: I still trust government data.

00:36:43.920 --> 00:36:48.560
[Guest 1]: So, if the government gives you data saying that this is the collection of GST, it's real.

00:36:49.600 --> 00:36:51.440
[Guest 1]: I don't think data is being fudged.

00:36:51.440 --> 00:36:56.240
[Guest 1]: What is happening in that speaks to the robustness of the statistical system,

00:36:56.240 --> 00:36:59.200
[Guest 1]: which is that they've not been able to start fudging that data.

00:36:59.840 --> 00:37:01.840
[Guest 1]: But, so there are two questions.

00:37:01.840 --> 00:37:05.440
[Guest 1]: There are two questions, so what is the data that I look at and what is the data that I

00:37:05.440 --> 00:37:07.280
[Guest 1]: think has problems with it?

00:37:07.280 --> 00:37:09.280
[Guest 1]: And this ties up to what she said earlier.

00:37:09.280 --> 00:37:17.920
[Guest 1]: So, if the government is not releasing employment data, I am looking at it through the CMIE lens.

00:37:18.640 --> 00:37:23.600
[Guest 1]: CMIE has been around as long as I've been around and I've never sensed an agenda.

00:37:24.320 --> 00:37:26.080
[Guest 1]: They are thoroughly professional.

00:37:26.080 --> 00:37:29.040
[Guest 1]: They have a reputation to defend.

00:37:29.040 --> 00:37:32.880
[Guest 1]: They don't have an economic agenda, as far as I know, or political agenda.

00:37:32.880 --> 00:37:33.920
[Guest 1]: I trust their data.

00:37:34.480 --> 00:37:40.640
[Guest 1]: And you know, you learn to look for continuities or discontinuities in data.

00:37:41.520 --> 00:37:48.880
[Guest 1]: When there are discontinuities or the data doesn't square with your view of reality,

00:37:48.880 --> 00:37:50.080
[Guest 1]: you're going to question it.

00:37:50.080 --> 00:37:51.040
[Guest 1]: I've not seen that.

00:37:51.680 --> 00:37:54.640
[Guest 1]: So, when it comes to employment, I look at CMIE data.

00:37:54.640 --> 00:37:59.760
[Guest 1]: When it comes to consumption, again, there's some data coming from pyramid studies.

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:01.680
[Guest 1]: There's some data coming from CMIE.

00:38:02.400 --> 00:38:07.040
[Guest 1]: There's RBI does a bi-monthly survey of consumer confidence.

00:38:07.040 --> 00:38:08.720
[Guest 1]: That is also an index into that.

00:38:09.360 --> 00:38:11.840
[Guest 1]: So, you have to look in a more rounded way.

00:38:13.040 --> 00:38:21.440
[Guest 1]: When it comes to the meta number, which is GDP, we know that this number is severely flawed.

00:38:21.440 --> 00:38:26.080
[Guest 1]: Severely flawed, let's even assume it's not flawed by intent.

00:38:26.800 --> 00:38:30.320
[Guest 1]: It is flawed by design, which is as follows.

00:38:31.120 --> 00:38:38.480
[Guest 1]: As she said, I can collect data as far as the formal sector is concerned every quarter.

00:38:39.360 --> 00:38:44.320
[Guest 1]: Because all the reports that all companies have to submit, so-called formal sector,

00:38:44.320 --> 00:38:48.480
[Guest 1]: there's not an exact mapping, but they have to file their returns every quarter,

00:38:48.480 --> 00:38:52.480
[Guest 1]: they pay their taxes, etc., etc. A good statistician can take that out

00:38:52.480 --> 00:38:54.480
[Guest 1]: and say the formal sector has grown by this much.

00:38:55.280 --> 00:39:02.000
[Guest 1]: Now, in the past, what you used to do, surveys, every five years, you surveyed the informal sector.

00:39:03.440 --> 00:39:08.640
[Guest 1]: And at the end of that, you said the informal sector can be projected to be X.

00:39:09.920 --> 00:39:11.760
[Guest 1]: We know that the formal sector is Y.

00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:14.640
[Guest 1]: We know the ratio between these.

00:39:14.640 --> 00:39:20.160
[Guest 1]: Now, till we do this survey again, we will assume that the ratio of X to Y remains the same.

00:39:21.040 --> 00:39:22.000
[Guest 1]: Fair enough.

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:24.240
[Guest 1]: I think that's a good method.

00:39:26.240 --> 00:39:35.360
[Guest 1]: The problem is that the last time you had a major survey of the informal sector was in 2015.

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:38.480
[Guest 1]: It should have been done again in 2020.

00:39:38.480 --> 00:39:39.600
[Guest 1]: It was not done.

00:39:39.600 --> 00:39:40.800
[Guest 1]: Completely understandable.

00:39:40.800 --> 00:39:45.920
[Guest 1]: Because it was COVID, etc., etc. Do it in 2021, you do it in 2022.

00:39:46.560 --> 00:39:48.960
[Guest 1]: So, again, I'm not suggesting there's an agenda.

00:39:48.960 --> 00:39:50.240
[Guest 1]: Fact is that you couldn't do it.

00:39:51.760 --> 00:39:58.160
[Guest 1]: What we also know, which is doubted as a great positive of the various measures

00:39:58.160 --> 00:40:01.440
[Guest 1]: taken by the government, is that the economy has got formalized.

00:40:02.800 --> 00:40:03.360
[Guest 1]: Right?

00:40:03.760 --> 00:40:06.320
[Guest 1]: What does that mean in mathematical terms?

00:40:06.320 --> 00:40:10.880
[Guest 1]: It means that the formal sector accounts for a larger percentage of the GDP.

00:40:12.160 --> 00:40:13.680
[Guest 1]: Otherwise, you can't say it's formalized.

00:40:14.400 --> 00:40:14.900
[Guest 1]: Right?

00:40:15.840 --> 00:40:19.280
[Guest 1]: This means that the earlier ratio will not apply any longer.

00:40:20.160 --> 00:40:24.880
[Guest 1]: The earlier ratio was, as it so happens, almost exactly 50-50.

00:40:25.840 --> 00:40:29.520
[Guest 1]: Which means that the formal sector was as large as the informal sector.

00:40:29.520 --> 00:40:31.680
[Guest 1]: So, you roughly multiplied by two.

00:40:31.680 --> 00:40:35.200
[Guest 1]: Now, how much has the informal sector shrunk?

00:40:35.200 --> 00:40:36.400
[Guest 1]: We know that it's shrunk.

00:40:37.920 --> 00:40:44.000
[Guest 1]: It was doubted, not in advance of, but in defense of demonetization.

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:45.280
[Guest 1]: We formalized the economy.

00:40:47.440 --> 00:40:53.040
[Guest 1]: It was, again, same situation with GST.

00:40:54.240 --> 00:40:58.480
[Guest 1]: In defense of, oh, but this economy has got more formalized.

00:40:58.480 --> 00:41:01.840
[Guest 1]: The people who are evading taxes are out of the loop.

00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:10.080
[Guest 1]: We know that the pandemic had the same impact because economic activity shrunk.

00:41:10.080 --> 00:41:12.400
[Guest 1]: The people with big balance sheets survived.

00:41:12.400 --> 00:41:16.160
[Guest 1]: Those who didn't shut down, they're more likely to be from the informal sector,

00:41:16.160 --> 00:41:17.920
[Guest 1]: because they're not banked, etc.

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:26.160
[Guest 1]: So, three events within a period of four years have led to the formalization of the economy.

00:41:26.160 --> 00:41:29.680
[Guest 1]: So, we know that that 50-50 number cannot be applied any longer.

00:41:30.560 --> 00:41:36.320
[Guest 1]: But the GDP numbers that we are using assume that that 50-50 number still applies.

00:41:38.240 --> 00:41:43.440
[Guest 1]: Now, you can say, and that's logical, that we don't know what ratio to apply.

00:41:44.960 --> 00:41:50.560
[Guest 1]: Should it be 50-50, or 48-52, or 30-70?

00:41:50.560 --> 00:41:51.200
[Guest 1]: We don't know.

00:41:51.200 --> 00:41:57.440
[Guest 1]: But I am certainly going to question a number which says that GDP is growing at 7%

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.640
[Guest 1]: if you're blowing up the formal sector by that number.

00:42:02.160 --> 00:42:08.720
[Guest 1]: Now, the SBI, in a recent survey, says the informal sector accounts for only 15% of the economy,

00:42:09.440 --> 00:42:10.320
[Guest 1]: from 50%.

00:42:11.360 --> 00:42:12.560
[Guest 1]: That sounds wild.

00:42:12.560 --> 00:42:13.520
[Guest 1]: It sounds wild to me.

00:42:13.520 --> 00:42:14.480
[Guest 1]: I don't believe it at all.

00:42:15.040 --> 00:42:16.800
[Guest 1]: What I'm saying is that we don't know the number.

00:42:16.800 --> 00:42:20.240
[Guest 1]: And therefore, I have to look at other stuff.

00:42:20.240 --> 00:42:28.480
[Guest 1]: But I can certainly say that that 5% growth is bound to be a huge overestimate.

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:33.200
[Guest 1]: And when you combine that with other data that you're getting,

00:42:33.200 --> 00:42:36.240
[Guest 1]: because now you're looking for hints, for clues from everywhere.

00:42:38.080 --> 00:42:43.840
[Guest 1]: We know from World Bank data, which was analyzed by the World Bank,

00:42:43.840 --> 00:42:49.760
[Guest 1]: World Bank data, which was analyzed by Pew in the US,

00:42:50.560 --> 00:42:55.520
[Guest 1]: study coincidentally was led by a classmate of mine from college,

00:42:56.800 --> 00:43:00.320
[Guest 1]: says that 75 million additional people

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:05.280
[Guest 1]: dropped below the poverty line in the last year and a half or two.

00:43:06.800 --> 00:43:11.360
[Guest 1]: You can't have that along with this kind of growth.

00:43:11.360 --> 00:43:12.640
[Guest 1]: There would have been some degrowth,

00:43:12.640 --> 00:43:16.960
[Guest 1]: even if those people only account for 2% of GDP.

00:43:16.960 --> 00:43:18.560
[Guest 1]: But there has been that degrowth.

00:43:22.720 --> 00:43:25.040
[Guest 1]: So you're bound to question these numbers.

00:43:26.160 --> 00:43:29.200
[Guest 1]: But nobody officially is trying to say,

00:43:29.200 --> 00:43:32.080
[Guest 1]: you know, we have to discount this number by such and such.

00:43:32.080 --> 00:43:37.280
[Guest 1]: Because as I said, in the absence of data, then narrative becomes everything.

00:43:37.280 --> 00:43:39.200
[Guest 1]: We will grow by 10% next year.

00:43:39.200 --> 00:43:43.440
[Guest 1]: We will grow by 7% in the long run. Then it's just narrative.

00:43:44.240 --> 00:43:48.800
[Guest 2]: Also, I think this is part of a larger shift that's happening globally, which is,

00:43:48.800 --> 00:43:51.520
[Guest 2]: you know, like you were saying 30 years ago,

00:43:51.520 --> 00:43:54.240
[Guest 2]: nobody questioned the truth because there was consensus,

00:43:54.240 --> 00:44:00.080
[Guest 2]: because the truth was determined by the experts, you know, the elites.

00:44:01.040 --> 00:44:07.360
[Guest 2]: Now, the whole political movement is anti-elite and anti-experts.

00:44:07.360 --> 00:44:13.760
[Guest 2]: Everybody hates anybody who's trained to do something, especially in economics.

00:44:15.040 --> 00:44:17.840
[Guest 2]: We like bureaucrats. We love historians.

00:44:17.840 --> 00:44:19.440
[Guest 2]: I'm not talking about the RBI governor.

00:44:19.440 --> 00:44:23.360
[Guest 2]: I'm talking about people who call themselves economists, but write only on history.

00:44:27.680 --> 00:44:31.680
[Guest 2]: But we don't want economists to talk about the economy.

00:44:31.680 --> 00:44:32.480
[Guest 2]: We don't trust them.

00:44:32.480 --> 00:44:40.400
[Guest 2]: We will trust anybody but an economist to tell us what should the economy be like.

00:44:42.640 --> 00:44:46.480
[Guest 2]: For the larger population to feel like this,

00:44:46.480 --> 00:44:49.520
[Guest 2]: it is an expression of frustration, not against economists,

00:44:49.520 --> 00:44:54.000
[Guest 2]: but against how things have not moved for them as much as they would have liked to,

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:55.840
[Guest 2]: you know, in so many years.

00:44:57.440 --> 00:45:01.360
[Guest 2]: People keep discussing about why economists have not delivered

00:45:01.360 --> 00:45:03.040
[Guest 2]: because politicians don't listen to them.

00:45:03.040 --> 00:45:10.000
[Guest 2]: So, you know, but the thing is that, you know, when you're sort of discrediting experts,

00:45:10.720 --> 00:45:14.480
[Guest 2]: you're opening up space for challenging narratives.

00:45:15.440 --> 00:45:20.400
[Guest 2]: You are turning economic debates into political debates.

00:45:20.400 --> 00:45:24.560
[Guest 2]: And that's how you're sort of trying to play the game of narratives.

00:45:25.200 --> 00:45:28.080
[Guest 2]: And therefore, data is not that important.

00:45:28.080 --> 00:45:30.720
[Guest 2]: Therefore, data collection is not that important.

00:45:30.720 --> 00:45:33.840
[Guest 2]: Therefore, narrative setting is more important.

00:45:33.840 --> 00:45:37.600
[Guest 2]: And nobody says, what do you mean when you say formal economy?

00:45:37.600 --> 00:45:41.120
[Guest 2]: That question no policymaker, no politician is asking.

00:45:41.760 --> 00:45:45.520
[Guest 2]: And people can bring out reports saying the formal sector shrunk without saying

00:45:45.520 --> 00:45:49.600
[Guest 2]: what they mean when they say informal economy is shrunk.

00:45:49.600 --> 00:45:50.960
[Guest 2]: I mean, I'll give you an example.

00:45:51.520 --> 00:45:57.040
[Guest 2]: In 2014, I had done an interview with somebody very senior in the IMF,

00:45:57.040 --> 00:46:01.600
[Guest 2]: who said, you know, we're very surprised at how quickly India has exited this grouping

00:46:01.600 --> 00:46:07.920
[Guest 2]: of the Fragile Five and all the data and he gave all the credit for it to the UPA government,

00:46:07.920 --> 00:46:11.440
[Guest 2]: the last few months of the UPA government and Darbhaiya Govt. Raghuram Rajan.

00:46:12.080 --> 00:46:19.360
[Guest 2]: And all the data that he, you know, gave was as on March 31, 2014.

00:46:19.360 --> 00:46:20.720
[Guest 2]: So this is before the government changed.

00:46:20.720 --> 00:46:26.480
[Guest 2]: This story, you know, made me very popular with when, you know, it was done

00:46:26.480 --> 00:46:27.680
[Guest 2]: after the government had changed.

00:46:27.680 --> 00:46:33.200
[Guest 2]: It made me very popular with people who now troll me because they thought, you know,

00:46:33.200 --> 00:46:36.400
[Guest 2]: because they didn't read the details and they thought, well, you know,

00:46:36.400 --> 00:46:40.240
[Guest 2]: it's a change of the government that has brought India out of the Fragile Five.

00:46:40.240 --> 00:46:46.400
[Guest 2]: And till today, the popular narrative is that this government has brought India out of

00:46:46.400 --> 00:46:51.360
[Guest 2]: out of the grouping of the Fragile Five. But nobody goes back to that story and reads,

00:46:51.360 --> 00:46:56.240
[Guest 2]: how did that happen? Who was the IMF talking about when they said that?

00:46:56.240 --> 00:46:59.440
[Guest 2]: So, you know, yeah, the truth data doesn't matter.

00:46:59.440 --> 00:47:04.480
[Guest 2]: Narrative matters. And so the question that you asked me is, how does,

00:47:05.360 --> 00:47:12.720
[Guest 2]: how does a journalist then do their job? Earlier, you know, most of us would only go to the experts.

00:47:12.720 --> 00:47:17.200
[Guest 2]: You know, now this is a good thing, I think, because there are some structural changes

00:47:17.200 --> 00:47:23.280
[Guest 2]: taking place in the economy after COVID, especially the amount of digitalization

00:47:23.280 --> 00:47:26.720
[Guest 2]: that is taking place. Sometimes I'm surprised where, you know.

00:47:26.720 --> 00:47:29.440
[Guest 2]: So that is, you know, a huge structural change.

00:47:29.440 --> 00:47:34.560
[Guest 2]: Now, it is going to change how we traditionally see the economy, economic growth,

00:47:34.560 --> 00:47:36.320
[Guest 2]: formal sector versus informal sector.

00:47:37.120 --> 00:47:40.800
[Guest 2]: You know, the experts must be working on this, I'm sure.

00:47:40.800 --> 00:47:46.400
[Guest 2]: But my worry is, you know, your narrative sounds very nice when you talk about these things,

00:47:46.400 --> 00:47:53.840
[Guest 2]: but what is policy doing to build on this? How are you bringing this into, you know,

00:47:53.840 --> 00:48:00.240
[Guest 2]: your policy decisions? Are you equipped to do that? You know, everybody, you know,

00:48:00.240 --> 00:48:01.680
[Guest 2]: the decision makers just seem so out of it.

00:48:01.680 --> 00:48:04.880
[Guest 1]: Well, you've already answered that, which is that there's nobody that we know who's

00:48:04.880 --> 00:48:09.840
[Guest 1]: making policy, you know. So, yeah, but the digitalization is coming.

00:48:09.840 --> 00:48:14.400
[Guest 1]: Digitalization is crazy. I realized this last winter.

00:48:15.200 --> 00:48:18.400
[Guest 1]: I typically spend a couple of weeks in Bangalore over the winter.

00:48:18.960 --> 00:48:21.200
[Guest 1]: And last year, because COVID, I spent longer time.

00:48:22.080 --> 00:48:30.400
[Guest 1]: And the guy from whom you buy tender coconut water out near Koramangala accepts Google Pay.

00:48:32.880 --> 00:48:37.040
[Guest 1]: I mean, that's really micro payment, right? 30 rupees you pay by Google Pay.

00:48:37.040 --> 00:48:42.080
[Guest 1]: And when I spent this year from April to September in our little village,

00:48:42.640 --> 00:48:47.520
[Guest 1]: the hardware store, four kilometers away, in a village of 500 people,

00:48:48.640 --> 00:48:52.240
[Guest 1]: I found that my wife was doing everything remotely.

00:48:52.240 --> 00:48:53.120
[Guest 1]: You don't need cash.

00:48:53.120 --> 00:48:55.200
[Guest 1]: She would order the stuff on the phone.

00:48:56.400 --> 00:49:00.560
[Guest 1]: The guy would put it onto the bus, which came once a day in the afternoon.

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:01.760
[Guest 1]: It would come on the bus.

00:49:01.760 --> 00:49:06.960
[Guest 1]: And of course, this being a little village, it would just be dumped at the bottom of our driveway.

00:49:06.960 --> 00:49:09.200
[Guest 1]: And it would be, you know, it's not going to go.

00:49:09.200 --> 00:49:11.280
[Guest 1]: We'll pick it up in the evening.

00:49:12.080 --> 00:49:16.000
[Guest 1]: And the bill would come along with the consignment and she'd transfer it by Google Pay.

00:49:16.640 --> 00:49:18.640
[Guest 1]: So, it's fantastic.

00:49:19.200 --> 00:49:22.800
[Guest 1]: But, like my sense is that this is a good thing.

00:49:22.800 --> 00:49:26.080
[Amit Varma]: But has the end come closer with the wrong means?

00:49:26.080 --> 00:49:32.320
[Amit Varma]: I don't think that this particular end has to do with demands or any of that.

00:49:32.320 --> 00:49:34.240
[Amit Varma]: It's just a natural flow that could have happened.

00:49:34.240 --> 00:49:38.560
[Guest 2]: Covid, I think it's because of the shock of Covid.

00:49:38.560 --> 00:49:43.360
[Guest 2]: I also feel that, you know, I'm all right if somebody wants to take credit for it.

00:49:43.360 --> 00:49:44.080
[Guest 2]: That's all right.

00:49:44.080 --> 00:49:46.080
[Guest 2]: What matters is that something good happened.

00:49:46.800 --> 00:49:53.040
[Guest 2]: But when something good happened, beyond using it to nourish your narrative,

00:49:53.040 --> 00:50:01.680
[Guest 2]: why not actually study it and, you know, be more, you know, have a more robust response to the change.

00:50:01.680 --> 00:50:02.960
[Guest 2]: Which you've already answered that.

00:50:02.960 --> 00:50:05.280
[Guest 1]: Because if you want to study it, you need experts.

00:50:05.280 --> 00:50:10.000
[Guest 1]: And you think experts are the last people you want to listen to.

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:13.360
[Guest 2]: So, you're sort of shooting yourself in the foot.

00:50:13.360 --> 00:50:15.360
[Guest 2]: My other question is kind of about mindset.

00:50:15.360 --> 00:50:17.200
[Amit Varma]: Like we were talking about formal and informal.

00:50:17.200 --> 00:50:21.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, I just want to dwell on this particular issue of, you know,

00:50:21.040 --> 00:50:25.120
[Guest 1]: I just want to dwell on this particular issue of who's making economic policy.

00:50:25.120 --> 00:50:26.720
[Guest 1]: And it's a broader issue.

00:50:26.720 --> 00:50:32.000
[Guest 1]: I have a very dear friend who was chief executive of a very large chemical company.

00:50:32.960 --> 00:50:41.120
[Guest 1]: And in the process of his work, both as an individual CEO, as well as being on the industry

00:50:41.120 --> 00:50:43.120
[Guest 1]: body and therefore lobbying.

00:50:43.120 --> 00:50:46.640
[Guest 1]: And, you know, he became very friendly with a particular secretary to the government of India.

00:50:46.640 --> 00:50:49.920
[Guest 1]: And they began talking about policy.

00:50:50.640 --> 00:50:58.960
[Guest 1]: This guy said to me, you know, when I have to write a note on policy, it doesn't go to my minister.

00:50:59.920 --> 00:51:00.880
[Guest 1]: It goes to the PMO.

00:51:01.600 --> 00:51:03.600
[Guest 1]: It goes on a blank piece of paper.

00:51:03.600 --> 00:51:05.040
[Guest 1]: It's not on my official email.

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:06.240
[Guest 1]: It's not on a letterhead.

00:51:07.520 --> 00:51:09.120
[Guest 1]: Who reads it in the PMO?

00:51:09.120 --> 00:51:10.000
[Guest 1]: I don't know.

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:11.280
[Guest 2]: What language do they use?

00:51:11.280 --> 00:51:12.320
[Guest 2]: Wait, wait, wait, wait.

00:51:13.360 --> 00:51:14.800
[Guest 1]: It goes to the PMO.

00:51:14.800 --> 00:51:18.800
[Guest 1]: It goes to the PMO, it comes back with notes scribbled on it, uninitialed.

00:51:18.800 --> 00:51:20.000
[Guest 1]: I don't know whose notes there are.

00:51:20.720 --> 00:51:24.400
[Guest 1]: Now I incorporate those notes into my policy.

00:51:24.400 --> 00:51:26.160
[Guest 1]: Now it goes through the official channels.

00:51:27.040 --> 00:51:34.160
[Guest 1]: So that if there was any mistake incorporated into the new policy, they'll say, but this

00:51:34.160 --> 00:51:35.040
[Guest 1]: came from the ministry.

00:51:35.600 --> 00:51:40.640
[Guest 1]: A secretary to the government of India does not know who is reading his policy suggestions

00:51:40.640 --> 00:51:41.600
[Guest 1]: and telling him what to do.

00:51:42.640 --> 00:51:44.400
[Guest 1]: So this is not just about economics.

00:51:44.400 --> 00:51:45.360
[Guest 1]: It's across the board.

00:51:46.400 --> 00:51:49.280
[Guest 1]: It's a black box in which policy is being made.

00:51:50.320 --> 00:51:51.280
[Amit Varma]: A black hole, rather.

00:51:52.080 --> 00:51:54.560
[Amit Varma]: You can open up a black box and figure out what happened.

00:51:56.560 --> 00:52:00.560
[Amit Varma]: So the question I was coming to is, you know, you mentioned informal, informal, formal,

00:52:00.560 --> 00:52:04.080
[Amit Varma]: informal, and we'll kind of, we can double click on that later and go into that in some

00:52:04.080 --> 00:52:04.960
[Amit Varma]: detail.

00:52:04.960 --> 00:52:11.600
[Amit Varma]: But at a meta level, it, you know, I've always felt that the way that issue, the way that

00:52:11.600 --> 00:52:16.560
[Amit Varma]: is framed is to me wrong, that people in the informal sector are doing something sinful,

00:52:16.560 --> 00:52:18.560
[Amit Varma]: they're evading tax, blah, blah, blah.

00:52:18.560 --> 00:52:20.000
[Amit Varma]: And I just feel that's wrong.

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:24.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, the informal sector is informal because it's been forced to be there because

00:52:24.880 --> 00:52:29.600
[Amit Varma]: the heavy hand of the law is just, you know, so oppressive that sometimes you don't have

00:52:29.600 --> 00:52:30.000
[Amit Varma]: a choice.

00:52:30.000 --> 00:52:32.720
[Amit Varma]: You just, you're in the informal sector, you're outside the system.

00:52:32.720 --> 00:52:36.960
[Amit Varma]: And of course, you're very small and all of that, all those things come into play.

00:52:36.960 --> 00:52:43.920
[Amit Varma]: Now, it seems to me that at some level that there is sort of this mindset within the government

00:52:43.920 --> 00:52:48.400
[Amit Varma]: that informal ko formal banana hai, number one, so we know exactly what's happening and

00:52:48.400 --> 00:52:54.880
[Amit Varma]: everything is in the clear light of day and make it formal not by removing all these restrictions

00:52:54.880 --> 00:53:00.480
[Amit Varma]: and by enabling ease of business, which allows them to come into the light, but through all

00:53:00.480 --> 00:53:01.920
[Amit Varma]: these different ways.

00:53:01.920 --> 00:53:06.160
[Amit Varma]: And secondly, one of the key metrics when people talk about how well the economy is

00:53:06.160 --> 00:53:07.840
[Amit Varma]: doing seems to be tax collections.

00:53:08.480 --> 00:53:12.560
[Amit Varma]: And I don't understand why that should be a metric because tax collections to me, let

00:53:12.560 --> 00:53:13.520
[Amit Varma]: me finish my question.

00:53:13.520 --> 00:53:18.640
[Amit Varma]: So tax collections to me are and sort of a transfer from the productive part of the economy

00:53:18.640 --> 00:53:20.560
[Amit Varma]: to the parasitic part of the economy.

00:53:20.560 --> 00:53:22.560
[Amit Varma]: So I don't know why that should be a metric.

00:53:22.560 --> 00:53:28.400
[Amit Varma]: But my question, therefore, is that, you know, in 91, it seemed that a fundamental mindset

00:53:28.400 --> 00:53:32.720
[Amit Varma]: shift that kind of happened, where policymakers figured out that we need to get out of the

00:53:32.720 --> 00:53:35.760
[Amit Varma]: way, people are smart, they'll take care of themselves.

00:53:35.760 --> 00:53:38.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, voluntary interactions will kick in, it's a positive sum game.

00:53:39.520 --> 00:53:45.840
[Amit Varma]: That seems to, if it was there at all, in any serious way, it kind of seems to have

00:53:45.840 --> 00:53:49.600
[Amit Varma]: sort of disappeared, where we still have the central planning mindset, and we want to control

00:53:49.600 --> 00:53:52.960
[Amit Varma]: everything, not just, and if we can't control reality, we'll control the narrative.

00:53:52.960 --> 00:53:53.920
[Amit Varma]: So I know I'm rambling a bit.

00:53:55.280 --> 00:53:56.800
[Guest 1]: I have a few reactions to that.

00:53:56.800 --> 00:54:04.080
[Guest 1]: Firstly, you know, where I come from, in terms of my economic ideologies, exactly as you

00:54:04.080 --> 00:54:06.480
[Guest 1]: do, it's not just parasitic.

00:54:06.480 --> 00:54:11.680
[Guest 1]: It's also, you know, as Ajay Shah talked about in his book and on your podcast, it

00:54:11.680 --> 00:54:17.920
[Guest 1]: has been demonstrated that revenue in the hands of government is one third as efficient

00:54:17.920 --> 00:54:20.480
[Guest 1]: as revenue in the hands of the private person, right?

00:54:20.480 --> 00:54:24.640
[Guest 1]: So it's, yeah, so it's not just parasitic, it's grossly inefficient.

00:54:24.640 --> 00:54:34.320
[Guest 1]: But to me, the even bigger problem, aside from inefficiency and so on and so forth,

00:54:34.320 --> 00:54:39.920
[Guest 1]: is the fact that 85% of the employment is in the informal sector.

00:54:40.880 --> 00:54:47.200
[Guest 1]: So when you start bashing the informal sector, first through demonetization, then through

00:54:47.200 --> 00:54:55.840
[Guest 1]: GST, then through pandemic, you're rendering vast swathes of the population unproductive.

00:54:55.840 --> 00:54:57.280
[Guest 1]: You're putting them out of work.

00:54:58.320 --> 00:55:00.480
[Guest 1]: You're taking money off their tables.

00:55:01.200 --> 00:55:06.800
[Guest 1]: And to some extent, then you're trying to replace it with these grand gestures of

00:55:09.040 --> 00:55:11.200
[Guest 1]: princely munificence, which it isn't.

00:55:12.880 --> 00:55:17.040
[Guest 1]: But you're taking away the dignity of people who were able to feed their families yesterday

00:55:17.040 --> 00:55:17.920
[Guest 1]: and they can't today.

00:55:19.360 --> 00:55:27.520
[Guest 1]: And we are about the lowest labor participation rate in the world is in India.

00:55:29.760 --> 00:55:37.120
[Guest 1]: Of adults between 80 and 65, what percentage of people take part in the economy?

00:55:37.120 --> 00:55:40.000
[Guest 1]: India is about the lowest in the world at 40%.

00:55:40.000 --> 00:55:47.200
[Guest 1]: It was 42 before COVID hit.

00:55:47.200 --> 00:55:48.800
[Guest 1]: It went down to like 36 now.

00:55:48.800 --> 00:55:50.160
[Guest 1]: It's still below 40.

00:55:54.080 --> 00:56:00.560
[Guest 1]: So if you don't grow, either you find a way to formalize and grow so rapidly, you have

00:56:00.560 --> 00:56:04.400
[Guest 1]: GDP growth rates of 10 and 12%, like China had for 30 years.

00:56:04.400 --> 00:56:05.520
[Guest 1]: There's a different story.

00:56:05.520 --> 00:56:09.680
[Guest 1]: You neither have that, nor do you ally the informal sector.

00:56:09.680 --> 00:56:17.040
[Guest 1]: You've got, and these are the longer term issues that worry me even more, that you are

00:56:17.040 --> 00:56:19.200
[Guest 1]: having, you know, she talked about a lost decade.

00:56:19.200 --> 00:56:24.560
[Guest 1]: My worry is about lost generations of young people.

00:56:25.920 --> 00:56:27.440
[Guest 1]: And I see those people.

00:56:27.440 --> 00:56:30.160
[Guest 1]: These are not just statistics for me.

00:56:30.160 --> 00:56:31.680
[Guest 1]: I understand statistics.

00:56:31.680 --> 00:56:33.120
[Guest 1]: I look at them carefully.

00:56:33.120 --> 00:56:34.320
[Guest 1]: I'm trained to look at them.

00:56:34.320 --> 00:56:35.840
[Guest 1]: But I see the people.

00:56:37.360 --> 00:56:44.080
[Guest 1]: These are 35 year old men whom I first interacted with when they were three and four and five

00:56:44.080 --> 00:56:44.640
[Guest 1]: years old.

00:56:46.160 --> 00:56:51.920
[Guest 1]: And I saw the hopes with which their parents, who were my neighbors, perhaps my employees,

00:56:54.320 --> 00:57:00.400
[Guest 1]: with which they put them into schooling and how they emerged with no hope.

00:57:00.400 --> 00:57:03.920
[Guest 1]: Two things let them down, and the two are intimately related.

00:57:05.360 --> 00:57:08.720
[Guest 1]: Because is education supply-led or demand-led?

00:57:09.520 --> 00:57:10.800
[Guest 1]: You know, we've talked about it often.

00:57:10.800 --> 00:57:12.480
[Guest 1]: You believe it's demand-led.

00:57:12.480 --> 00:57:13.600
[Guest 1]: To some extent, I agree.

00:57:13.600 --> 00:57:14.160
[Guest 1]: Not fully.

00:57:14.160 --> 00:57:15.040
[Guest 1]: We differ on that.

00:57:15.040 --> 00:57:21.360
[Guest 1]: But on the demand side, if there's no employment being created, your incentive to pursue high

00:57:21.360 --> 00:57:23.920
[Guest 1]: quality education vanishes.

00:57:23.920 --> 00:57:25.120
[Guest 1]: And that's certainly the case.

00:57:25.120 --> 00:57:33.760
[Guest 1]: All these young men are either unemployed or underemployed, and I'm seeing them.

00:57:33.760 --> 00:57:37.440
[Guest 1]: I saw them when they were five, I saw them 16, I saw them when they were 20, they're

00:57:37.440 --> 00:57:38.480
[Guest 1]: now in their 30s.

00:57:38.480 --> 00:57:43.200
[Guest 1]: And when you speak of lost generations, the point is that losing generations at this point

00:57:43.200 --> 00:57:47.680
[Amit Varma]: in time, when we are having this demographic movement where what was a demographic dividend

00:57:47.680 --> 00:57:50.400
[Amit Varma]: is becoming a demographic disaster is even worse.

00:57:50.400 --> 00:57:50.960
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

00:57:50.960 --> 00:58:05.280
[Guest 2]: Also, you know, there's more fundamental thing, an increase in GST collections may not necessarily

00:58:05.280 --> 00:58:09.040
[Guest 2]: be an indicator of growing GDP.

00:58:09.040 --> 00:58:12.720
[Guest 2]: It could probably just be that companies have, you know, raised their selling price.

00:58:13.760 --> 00:58:18.400
[Guest 2]: I mean, somebody needs to study that and, you know, decipher the data for us.

00:58:18.400 --> 00:58:21.440
[Guest 2]: And, you know, the other thing is that, you know,

00:58:21.440 --> 00:58:26.480
[Guest 1]: Don't find that data very clear, which is that the increase in GST over the last two

00:58:26.480 --> 00:58:29.120
[Guest 1]: years is barely more than what inflation has been.

00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:31.680
[Guest 1]: So in real terms, it's not great.

00:58:33.280 --> 00:58:34.000
[Amit Varma]: Regardless, yes.

00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:34.560
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

00:58:34.560 --> 00:58:39.680
[Guest 2]: And the other thing is that, so, you know, multiple things happen and it, which is why,

00:58:39.680 --> 00:58:44.080
[Guest 2]: you know, it's very difficult sometimes, even for the experts, people are trained to do

00:58:44.080 --> 00:58:46.000
[Guest 2]: it to understand what goes on in the economy.

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:50.720
[Guest 2]: And, you know, there's all this oversimplification in the narrative that happens is very, very

00:58:50.720 --> 00:58:52.640
[Guest 2]: harmful because of that.

00:58:52.640 --> 00:58:59.520
[Guest 2]: Like, for instance, for years, there was this whole politics around FDI and retail.

00:59:00.400 --> 00:59:07.040
[Guest 2]: Now, Amazon is this much hated big company, and we have cabinet ministers who have declared

00:59:07.040 --> 00:59:15.040
[Guest 2]: the Quit India movement, you know, and, but, well, the only sector in which employment

00:59:15.040 --> 00:59:20.080
[Guest 2]: generation is happening as of today is the online retail sector.

00:59:20.080 --> 00:59:24.720
[Guest 2]: And it is not happening, and which is also leading to formalization.

00:59:24.720 --> 00:59:30.000
[Guest 2]: All of your small shops, you know, around you have all tied into Amazon.

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:31.920
[Guest 2]: You would have also seen this happening.

00:59:32.560 --> 00:59:35.600
[Guest 2]: And, you know, their business is growing and it's a win-win at the moment.

00:59:35.600 --> 00:59:38.400
[Guest 2]: Since Amazon is such a large company, it has such a bad reputation globally.

00:59:38.400 --> 00:59:41.920
[Guest 2]: We don't know if this, you know, equation will remain win-win, but that's where the

00:59:41.920 --> 00:59:43.680
[Guest 2]: role of policy and regulation comes in.

00:59:43.680 --> 00:59:48.240
[Guest 2]: But so far, it has happened organically on its own because the market forces are operating.

00:59:48.880 --> 00:59:53.760
[Guest 2]: And it is happening in almost opposite of what the concerns of the politicians for years

00:59:53.760 --> 00:59:54.240
[Guest 2]: have been.

00:59:54.800 --> 01:00:00.240
[Guest 2]: And all the support they mobilized from exactly these people, you know, saying that Amazon

01:00:00.240 --> 01:00:04.560
[Guest 2]: is your, I mean, whatever, Western retail giants are your biggest enemies.

01:00:04.560 --> 01:00:08.960
[Guest 2]: My point is that, you know, this could have happened sooner.

01:00:08.960 --> 01:00:11.120
[Guest 2]: It could have happened in a more regulated way.

01:00:11.120 --> 01:00:19.680
[Guest 2]: It can happen in wider parts of the country if policymakers were taking better, well-informed

01:00:19.680 --> 01:00:22.160
[Guest 2]: decisions and not simply doing politics.

01:00:23.040 --> 01:00:27.040
[Guest 2]: I think almost always on the basis of not even understanding what they're talking about.

01:00:27.840 --> 01:00:30.080
[Guest 2]: This is a big example of it.

01:00:30.080 --> 01:00:34.000
[Guest 2]: And, you know, this is what to me is most worrying.

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:38.560
[Guest 2]: To me, what is more, you want to do a narrative, you want to do your politics.

01:00:38.560 --> 01:00:39.520
[Guest 2]: That's all right.

01:00:39.520 --> 01:00:45.280
[Guest 2]: As long as, you know, deep in your ministries, you were doing your policymaking, you know,

01:00:45.280 --> 01:00:49.760
[Guest 2]: like policy wonks and getting, you know, applying your minds to these things.

01:00:51.840 --> 01:00:53.440
[Guest 2]: We don't see any evidence of that.

01:00:53.440 --> 01:00:58.080
[Guest 2]: And to me, that is more worrying, you know, not the polarization and not everything.

01:00:58.080 --> 01:01:01.120
[Guest 2]: Because why is it so easy to polarize?

01:01:01.120 --> 01:01:04.960
[Guest 2]: Why is it easy to do politics all the time and mislead people?

01:01:04.960 --> 01:01:07.920
[Guest 2]: Because that's all that, you know, goes on.

01:01:07.920 --> 01:01:11.440
[Guest 2]: People don't see the truth because, you know, you're not doing policymaking.

01:01:12.400 --> 01:01:15.680
[Amit Varma]: I love the phrase you just used, deep in your ministries.

01:01:15.680 --> 01:01:19.120
[Amit Varma]: That sounds like the kind of phrase like China Meevil or a fantasy fiction writer,

01:01:19.120 --> 01:01:21.200
[Amit Varma]: deep in your ministries, kind of.

01:01:21.200 --> 01:01:22.400
[Guest 1]: Or even Brave New World.

01:01:23.200 --> 01:01:23.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:01:23.680 --> 01:01:26.560
[Amit Varma]: All suitably dystopian.

01:01:26.560 --> 01:01:32.720
[Guest 2]: So that, you know, that comes from how the non-bloc is organized, you know, who sits

01:01:32.720 --> 01:01:36.640
[Guest 2]: on the ground floor, you know, who are the people who sit closer to the minister's office.

01:01:36.640 --> 01:01:40.800
[Guest 2]: So, yeah, unconsciously, I think that's what I'm talking about.

01:01:40.800 --> 01:01:41.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:01:41.040 --> 01:01:43.440
[Amit Varma]: It's a very resonant phrase, you know, deep in your ministries.

01:01:43.440 --> 01:01:43.840
[Amit Varma]: You could have.

01:01:44.720 --> 01:01:45.920
[Guest 1]: I've never had the privilege of.

01:01:46.960 --> 01:01:50.960
[Amit Varma]: Not these ministries, but I'm imagining, like, I remember when I first came to Bombay,

01:01:50.960 --> 01:01:54.640
[Amit Varma]: I was obviously blown away by the scale of it because I'd never been in such a big city.

01:01:54.640 --> 01:01:58.560
[Amit Varma]: And I remember going to Dadar station and it took me half an hour just to find the correct

01:01:58.560 --> 01:02:02.800
[Amit Varma]: platform because Dadar station is where all the different lines, harbor line, central line,

01:02:02.800 --> 01:02:04.960
[Amit Varma]: which they all kind of converge.

01:02:04.960 --> 01:02:07.680
[Amit Varma]: And it was like being inside this giant video game.

01:02:07.680 --> 01:02:10.720
[Amit Varma]: Like, you remember the video games of the 90s, Prince and all of that.

01:02:10.720 --> 01:02:14.000
[Amit Varma]: You're navigating on those or Wolfenstein.

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:16.720
[Amit Varma]: And it was like being in this giant video game.

01:02:16.720 --> 01:02:21.360
[Amit Varma]: And I thought a video game set in Dadar would be so incredible with this labyrinthine and

01:02:21.360 --> 01:02:23.520
[Amit Varma]: multi-level shit happening all over the place.

01:02:24.240 --> 01:02:26.160
[Amit Varma]: And of course, those forms of people.

01:02:26.160 --> 01:02:29.200
[Guest 2]: You should visit finance ministry some point in time.

01:02:29.200 --> 01:02:30.720
[Unknown]: That's what you made it sound like.

01:02:30.720 --> 01:02:31.600
[Unknown]: Yeah, yeah, it is.

01:02:31.600 --> 01:02:35.360
[Guest 2]: There is a basement, you know, where there are these documents, which I don't think anybody's

01:02:35.360 --> 01:02:36.960
[Unknown]: touched for a million years.

01:02:36.960 --> 01:02:42.240
[Guest 2]: You know, there's a sort of kind of a courtyard in the center, on the top floors, you know,

01:02:42.240 --> 01:02:43.360
[Guest 2]: all the section officers.

01:02:43.360 --> 01:02:46.720
[Unknown]: It's, somebody should write about it, actually.

01:02:48.080 --> 01:02:50.880
[Guest 2]: Since we are talking about this, this is not related to our conversation.

01:02:50.880 --> 01:02:56.240
[Guest 2]: But an interesting thing is that Lord Mountbatten's office is in finance ministry still.

01:02:56.240 --> 01:02:59.040
[Guest 2]: There is a plaque that, you know, where the CBDD chairman sits.

01:02:59.040 --> 01:03:01.440
[Guest 2]: So it says the, what was he?

01:03:01.440 --> 01:03:03.600
[Guest 2]: The Supreme Commander of the Second World War.

01:03:04.800 --> 01:03:08.560
[Guest 2]: That is the office and the balcony sometimes opened, you know, where he used to sit and

01:03:08.560 --> 01:03:11.120
[Guest 2]: look at the Viceroy's, this thing.

01:03:11.120 --> 01:03:12.160
[Amit Varma]: So his ghost is there.

01:03:15.120 --> 01:03:16.480
[Guest 2]: It's all over India now.

01:03:16.480 --> 01:03:21.520
[Unknown]: Mountbatten's office still existing in North York reminds me of, reminds me of CCA.

01:03:21.520 --> 01:03:23.040
[Amit Varma]: You must be knowing about CCA, right?

01:03:24.080 --> 01:03:24.880
[Amit Varma]: CCA?

01:03:24.880 --> 01:03:26.480
[Amit Varma]: Okay, let me tell you about CCA.

01:03:26.480 --> 01:03:30.720
[Amit Varma]: So sometime in the 1980s, and to give credit where credit is due, I think Vivek Debroy

01:03:30.720 --> 01:03:32.720
[Amit Varma]: first wrote about this in one of his books.

01:03:32.720 --> 01:03:38.240
[Amit Varma]: So sometime in the 1980s, a department in the Tamil Nadu ministry called the CCA, this

01:03:38.240 --> 01:03:43.360
[Amit Varma]: gentleman in the Tamil Nadu ministry, who was part of this department called the CCA,

01:03:43.360 --> 01:03:46.000
[Amit Varma]: they apply for a raise in their budgets.

01:03:46.560 --> 01:03:51.440
[Amit Varma]: So when it goes to whatever committee looks into these things, they decide to look into

01:03:51.440 --> 01:03:52.960
[Amit Varma]: ki ye, what is the CCA?

01:03:52.960 --> 01:03:53.360
[Amit Varma]: Hai kya?

01:03:53.360 --> 01:03:53.920
[Amit Varma]: What do they do?

01:03:53.920 --> 01:03:59.360
[Amit Varma]: So here's the history of the CCA, that the Second World War breaks out, we have to go

01:03:59.360 --> 01:04:00.480
[Amit Varma]: back to that period.

01:04:00.480 --> 01:04:02.240
[Amit Varma]: The Second World War breaks out.

01:04:02.240 --> 01:04:06.800
[Amit Varma]: And part of the result of the Second World War breaking out is that trade routes between

01:04:06.800 --> 01:04:08.560
[Amit Varma]: Cuba and England are broken.

01:04:08.560 --> 01:04:13.280
[Amit Varma]: Now, Winston Churchill, you know, who is at the helm of the English effort to save the

01:04:13.280 --> 01:04:17.280
[Amit Varma]: Western world, which he successfully manages, loves cigars.

01:04:17.280 --> 01:04:20.560
[Amit Varma]: And the best cigars in the world, according to him, are from Cuba, he can no longer get

01:04:20.560 --> 01:04:20.960
[Amit Varma]: them.

01:04:20.960 --> 01:04:26.400
[Amit Varma]: The second best cigars in the world are from Trichinarapalli or whatever, it's from Tamil

01:04:26.400 --> 01:04:26.960
[Amit Varma]: Nadu.

01:04:26.960 --> 01:04:33.920
[Amit Varma]: So a department is set up in the imperial ministry called CCA, Churchill Cigar Assistant.

01:04:33.920 --> 01:04:35.120
[Unknown]: Wow, I didn't know that.

01:04:35.120 --> 01:04:40.560
[Amit Varma]: And the World War ends, and India becomes independent, and Churchill dies, and decades

01:04:40.560 --> 01:04:41.280
[Amit Varma]: pass.

01:04:41.280 --> 01:04:48.320
[Amit Varma]: And that department still is getting a budget, is still running until someday some mad moron

01:04:48.320 --> 01:04:53.280
[Amit Varma]: within that department decides to apply for an increase in the budget.

01:04:53.280 --> 01:05:00.400
[Guest 2]: So this is what, Amit, governments have always functioned like this.

01:05:00.400 --> 01:05:03.680
[Guest 2]: This is just a difference in degree, you know, like what you're saying.

01:05:03.680 --> 01:05:08.640
[Guest 2]: I also recognize that these problems go beyond the last, you know, decade.

01:05:08.640 --> 01:05:16.160
[Guest 2]: It's just the slide, you know, has just sort of really become really quick paced and worse

01:05:16.160 --> 01:05:16.720
[Guest 2]: now.

01:05:16.720 --> 01:05:23.040
[Guest 2]: Yeah, you know, I mean, people think, you know, when budget is made, you know, officials

01:05:23.040 --> 01:05:27.280
[Guest 2]: must be sitting looking at every entry, you know, how much is this department getting?

01:05:28.080 --> 01:05:30.000
[Guest 2]: You know, it's, it's not like that.

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:35.440
[Guest 2]: What they'll do is they'll just take all the heads, apply a certain, you know, increase

01:05:35.440 --> 01:05:40.240
[Guest 2]: multiplier, that it doesn't even get discussed, you know, these things are like, sometimes

01:05:40.240 --> 01:05:42.080
[Guest 2]: done really on the tips of their fingers.

01:05:42.080 --> 01:05:48.560
[Amit Varma]: And also, you know, all of this Mountbatten's office in North Bloc, or the CCA in the government

01:05:48.560 --> 01:05:54.320
[Amit Varma]: seem to me like metaphorically true for mindsets as well, that we stay tied to old mindsets

01:05:54.320 --> 01:05:59.440
[Amit Varma]: of the past, and don't change to recognize new realities, which is incredibly important,

01:05:59.440 --> 01:06:03.200
[Amit Varma]: especially in modern times where reality itself is changing so fast, the economy is changing

01:06:03.200 --> 01:06:04.000
[Amit Varma]: so fast.

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:07.760
[Guest 2]: The whole discussion we had last time I came to your show on Pranam Mukherjee taking finance

01:06:07.760 --> 01:06:13.040
[Guest 2]: mystery backwards, we are seeing that with Atmanirbhar and, you know, the trade policy

01:06:13.040 --> 01:06:17.600
[Guest 2]: and so many other things, you know, the return of the inspector Raj when these rules have

01:06:17.600 --> 01:06:23.760
[Guest 2]: come out for e-commerce, you know, how government officials can ask questions, everything is

01:06:23.760 --> 01:06:31.680
[Guest 2]: regressing back to the pre 1991 sort of mindset, because that is so deeply embedded into the

01:06:31.680 --> 01:06:37.280
[Guest 2]: way rules and regulations are written, shaping how bureaucrats think, shaping how politicians

01:06:37.280 --> 01:06:39.760
[Guest 2]: think 1991 happened.

01:06:39.760 --> 01:06:44.400
[Guest 2]: But, you know, everybody says that, you know, what it did is they forged a new consensus.

01:06:44.400 --> 01:06:50.640
[Guest 2]: And after that, the speed of change in policy, modernization of policy may have varied.

01:06:50.640 --> 01:06:55.360
[Guest 2]: But big, big thing that was one was that across political shades, there was consensus that

01:06:55.360 --> 01:06:58.160
[Guest 2]: this is the direction we will move in.

01:06:58.960 --> 01:07:04.640
[Guest 2]: I'm not so sure that, you know, there is that consensus anymore, if it was even in the first

01:07:04.640 --> 01:07:05.200
[Amit Varma]: place.

01:07:05.200 --> 01:07:08.960
[Amit Varma]: It's there's almost a poignant note in this that Ajay Shah, who's been on the show and

01:07:08.960 --> 01:07:12.560
[Amit Varma]: has written a great book in service of the Republic, one of the essential books in the

01:07:12.560 --> 01:07:16.000
[Amit Varma]: Indian economy, along with another one we'll talk about soon, once came on the show, it

01:07:16.000 --> 01:07:16.720
[Amit Varma]: was very poignant.

01:07:16.720 --> 01:07:20.880
[Amit Varma]: And he said that the reason I wrote that book, the reason I wrote that book is because there

01:07:20.880 --> 01:07:25.280
[Amit Varma]: were a certain number of people within government, within the policy circles, within whatever,

01:07:25.840 --> 01:07:30.640
[Amit Varma]: who were looking ahead, who, you know, had discarded the dogmas of the past and looking

01:07:30.640 --> 01:07:32.720
[Amit Varma]: ahead and wanted to make things better.

01:07:32.720 --> 01:07:34.480
[Amit Varma]: And those people were dying out.

01:07:34.480 --> 01:07:37.680
[Amit Varma]: And he said, I want to leave something for the next generation.

01:07:37.680 --> 01:07:41.760
[Amit Varma]: I want to leave something so that there can be more of us and more to this.

01:07:41.760 --> 01:07:45.120
[Amit Varma]: And I found it very inspiring and sad at the same time.

01:07:45.120 --> 01:07:47.440
[Amit Varma]: Some were dying, some were eased out.

01:07:47.440 --> 01:07:49.120
[Amit Varma]: Some were dying, some were eased out.

01:07:49.120 --> 01:07:54.000
[Amit Varma]: It's interesting, like there is that old phrase that paradigms change one death at a time.

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:58.800
[Amit Varma]: So you can't change minds, people change and a younger generation will do things differently.

01:07:58.800 --> 01:08:03.760
[Amit Varma]: Except that that hasn't happened, that there was a temporary moment of change.

01:08:03.760 --> 01:08:07.840
[Amit Varma]: And the people who believed in that change are kind of gone.

01:08:07.840 --> 01:08:13.440
[Guest 1]: But it's also true, though, of course, is a much debated issue, whether how much we

01:08:13.440 --> 01:08:19.120
[Guest 1]: believed in that change and how much it was forced upon us by circumstances, by a fiscal

01:08:19.120 --> 01:08:24.800
[Guest 1]: crisis, by a foreign exchange crisis, by the fact that we needed to tap into international

01:08:24.800 --> 01:08:28.320
[Guest 1]: loans and a lot of policy changes were forced on us by that.

01:08:28.320 --> 01:08:33.200
[Guest 2]: But I agree, you know, with Mantek Singhalwalia, when he says that it just wasn't sold.

01:08:33.200 --> 01:08:35.040
[Guest 2]: You see, people are not opposed to change.

01:08:35.040 --> 01:08:39.520
[Guest 2]: People like we just discussed, people are willing to move into digital forms of payment,

01:08:39.520 --> 01:08:40.720
[Guest 2]: for instance.

01:08:40.720 --> 01:08:44.320
[Guest 2]: So when it comes to technology, which makes their lives easier because it's so easy to

01:08:44.320 --> 01:08:46.560
[Guest 2]: demonstrate it, people are very open to change.

01:08:47.120 --> 01:08:54.720
[Guest 2]: If they're not open to change in wonky policies, it's because it has not been explained to

01:08:54.720 --> 01:08:56.640
[Guest 2]: them how it is good for them.

01:08:56.640 --> 01:08:59.600
[Guest 2]: And that is the failure of the politicians.

01:08:59.600 --> 01:09:01.040
[Guest 1]: The farm law is a clear example, right?

01:09:01.040 --> 01:09:01.600
[Guest 1]: Yeah, yeah.

01:09:01.600 --> 01:09:02.100
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:09:03.360 --> 01:09:10.400
[Guest 1]: You know, people from our side of the fence, meaning who believe that the role of a government

01:09:10.400 --> 01:09:14.320
[Guest 1]: needs to be limited, that subsidies need to be limited, etc.

01:09:14.320 --> 01:09:15.920
[Amit Varma]: Farmers need to be empowered with choice.

01:09:16.800 --> 01:09:17.600
[Guest 1]: Not just that.

01:09:19.840 --> 01:09:24.000
[Guest 1]: That there's several levels, there's several layers of them.

01:09:24.000 --> 01:09:28.800
[Guest 1]: And one of those layers is that it was decided at the time of the Constitution that agriculture

01:09:28.800 --> 01:09:30.320
[Guest 1]: should basically be a state subject.

01:09:30.880 --> 01:09:34.720
[Guest 1]: This MSP is not attainable in the long run.

01:09:35.280 --> 01:09:38.560
[Guest 1]: We've just accumulated so much dead stock.

01:09:39.920 --> 01:09:45.120
[Guest 1]: The fact that it has to go is a given, but it needs to be negotiated.

01:09:45.120 --> 01:09:46.320
[Guest 1]: It was not negotiated.

01:09:46.320 --> 01:09:48.720
[Guest 1]: Now you've got this huge political impasse sitting over there.

01:09:48.720 --> 01:09:57.360
[Guest 1]: And because that impasse has become so, so intractable, you have this horrendous spectacle

01:09:59.120 --> 01:10:08.000
[Guest 1]: of a cavalcade, which is mustered by a central minister's son, mowing down innocent farmers.

01:10:09.280 --> 01:10:10.480
[Guest 1]: It's only because of that.

01:10:11.360 --> 01:10:13.760
[Guest 1]: It's because you created an impasse.

01:10:13.760 --> 01:10:20.240
[Guest 1]: This should, as a policy wonk, I'm the first person to say that agriculture needs to be

01:10:20.240 --> 01:10:20.880
[Guest 1]: reformed.

01:10:20.880 --> 01:10:22.960
[Guest 1]: Agricultural policy needs to be reformed.

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:25.520
[Guest 1]: But it's got to be political.

01:10:25.520 --> 01:10:26.720
[Guest 1]: It's got to be negotiated.

01:10:27.440 --> 01:10:28.960
[Guest 1]: It was just announced one day.

01:10:28.960 --> 01:10:33.040
[Guest 1]: You see the difference between narrative and actually consensus building?

01:10:33.040 --> 01:10:37.600
[Guest 2]: In fact, I did an episode on the farm laws with Ajay and we both agreed, obviously, with

01:10:37.600 --> 01:10:40.480
[Amit Varma]: everything that you're saying, that that is a tragedy.

01:10:40.480 --> 01:10:45.440
[Amit Varma]: But you could change a couple of things about the farm laws, but economically, it's fine.

01:10:45.440 --> 01:10:46.000
[Amit Varma]: It's great.

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:47.440
[Amit Varma]: It's a move in the right direction.

01:10:47.440 --> 01:10:50.000
[Amit Varma]: But the politics is disastrous.

01:10:50.000 --> 01:10:51.360
[Amit Varma]: It's just tearing us apart.

01:10:51.360 --> 01:10:52.560
[Amit Varma]: It's disastrous.

01:10:52.560 --> 01:10:57.600
[Amit Varma]: And it's so ironic because typically what politicians excel at is getting the politics

01:10:57.600 --> 01:10:59.200
[Amit Varma]: right and the economics wrong.

01:10:59.200 --> 01:11:01.600
[Amit Varma]: And this is practically, literally the opposite.

01:11:01.600 --> 01:11:03.840
[Amit Varma]: I'm making two points.

01:11:03.840 --> 01:11:07.040
[Guest 1]: One is this one, which I agree with 100%.

01:11:07.040 --> 01:11:16.400
[Guest 1]: The other is that when it comes to agriculture, because the agricultural scenario is so different

01:11:16.400 --> 01:11:19.680
[Guest 1]: in different parts of the country, you can't have one policy.

01:11:19.680 --> 01:11:20.180
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:11:20.800 --> 01:11:22.160
[Guest 1]: Needs much deeper study.

01:11:22.160 --> 01:11:30.080
[Guest 1]: For example, I would say, top down, first principles, which is that the government should

01:11:30.080 --> 01:11:34.560
[Guest 1]: have no role as far as agricultural markets is concerned.

01:11:34.560 --> 01:11:37.280
[Guest 1]: A very simple statement to make.

01:11:37.280 --> 01:11:45.440
[Guest 1]: Now, this agricultural model bill was talked about 2003 or something like that, right?

01:11:45.440 --> 01:11:53.680
[Guest 1]: Only one state, the last state on earth you would expect, which is Bihar, took one major

01:11:53.680 --> 01:11:57.200
[Guest 1]: element of it and they said, no government mandis any longer.

01:11:57.200 --> 01:12:00.320
[Guest 1]: From a theoretical point of view, great.

01:12:00.320 --> 01:12:03.120
[Guest 1]: What did it result in?

01:12:03.120 --> 01:12:13.200
[Guest 1]: It resulted in a lowering of average price for farmers in Bihar, because a lot of mandis

01:12:13.200 --> 01:12:14.240
[Guest 1]: wound up.

01:12:14.240 --> 01:12:22.640
[Guest 1]: And so now the average distance from the farmer to the mandi went up, access to markets went

01:12:22.640 --> 01:12:23.680
[Guest 1]: down.

01:12:23.680 --> 01:12:25.200
[Guest 1]: You had two things.

01:12:25.200 --> 01:12:27.200
[Guest 1]: One is the average price came down.

01:12:27.200 --> 01:12:31.760
[Guest 1]: Secondly, the scatter in price went up, because those who were further got lower prices.

01:12:31.760 --> 01:12:35.120
[Guest 1]: Those who were closer got better prices.

01:12:35.120 --> 01:12:38.800
[Guest 1]: Now, I can still say, that's how it should be.

01:12:38.800 --> 01:12:43.120
[Guest 1]: If your farm is not located close enough to markets, you should get a lower price.

01:12:43.120 --> 01:12:44.880
[Guest 1]: You shouldn't be farming there.

01:12:44.880 --> 01:12:47.040
[Guest 1]: I can say that.

01:12:47.040 --> 01:12:49.360
[Guest 1]: Then this leads to another question.

01:12:49.360 --> 01:12:52.880
[Guest 1]: Why are the farmers in that situation?

01:12:52.880 --> 01:12:57.280
[Guest 1]: They're in that situation because there's no industry in Bihar.

01:12:57.280 --> 01:13:00.800
[Amit Varma]: And you're not allowed to sell agricultural land anyway for non-agricultural land.

01:13:00.800 --> 01:13:07.120
[Guest 1]: So when you have a mess at every level, who should carry the burden for it?

01:13:07.760 --> 01:13:12.560
[Guest 1]: You've ended up in a situation where the poorest people are carrying the burden, which is the

01:13:12.560 --> 01:13:13.280
[Guest 1]: small farmer.

01:13:14.880 --> 01:13:17.520
[Guest 1]: So from first principles, I can say good thing.

01:13:17.520 --> 01:13:20.960
[Guest 1]: But when you actually see the misery on the ground, you have to say, look, there's got

01:13:20.960 --> 01:13:21.920
[Guest 1]: to be negotiated.

01:13:24.000 --> 01:13:26.800
[Guest 1]: Anybody, you need to create an exit policy for them.

01:13:26.800 --> 01:13:34.560
[Guest 1]: So you can't do this by railroading a law through and look at the mess in Rajya Sabha.

01:13:36.240 --> 01:13:45.200
[Guest 1]: The voice vote, people are saying, and there is confusion about whether the, look how messy

01:13:45.200 --> 01:13:45.760
[Guest 1]: it was.

01:13:46.320 --> 01:13:48.480
[Guest 1]: Were the Rajya Sabha MPs in their chair or not?

01:13:49.120 --> 01:13:50.640
[Guest 1]: Were they allowed to vote or not?

01:13:50.640 --> 01:13:53.280
[Guest 1]: This is not the kind of stuff which you should be debating, right?

01:13:53.280 --> 01:13:56.320
[Guest 1]: Procedures should be clean, transparent.

01:13:56.320 --> 01:13:57.600
[Guest 1]: It shouldn't even come to that.

01:14:00.240 --> 01:14:13.840
[Guest 1]: At a meta level, major bills, which have been negotiated in Parliament in the last UPA government,

01:14:15.360 --> 01:14:20.640
[Guest 1]: something like 46% of bills were sent to expert committees.

01:14:20.640 --> 01:14:21.920
[Guest 1]: Sent to expert committees.

01:14:23.600 --> 01:14:25.440
[Guest 1]: Earlier on, it was as high as 70.

01:14:26.560 --> 01:14:33.200
[Guest 1]: In this Rajya Sabha, 11% of bills were sent to expert committee, which is a larger point,

01:14:33.200 --> 01:14:35.200
[Guest 2]: not just economics, across the board.

01:14:35.200 --> 01:14:35.920
[Guest 2]: I know best.

01:14:36.960 --> 01:14:37.920
[Guest 2]: That's the whole approach.

01:14:38.800 --> 01:14:39.360
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:14:39.360 --> 01:14:41.760
[Guest 1]: So there is no space for debate.

01:14:41.760 --> 01:14:44.000
[Guest 1]: There is no reason to have experts.

01:14:44.000 --> 01:14:47.360
[Guest 1]: It has been decided, Parliament doesn't exist, right?

01:14:47.360 --> 01:14:49.120
[Amit Varma]: In terms of what it's supposed to do.

01:14:49.120 --> 01:14:53.840
[Amit Varma]: You can run it from an Excel sheet, because anti-defection law, you decide how each MP votes.

01:14:54.880 --> 01:14:57.680
[Amit Varma]: It's like shifting from one equilibrium to another.

01:14:57.680 --> 01:15:04.560
[Amit Varma]: We can agree on what the ideal state of things should be where you empower farmers with choice,

01:15:04.560 --> 01:15:08.720
[Amit Varma]: you don't have the government playing a part and creating its monopolies and being the middleman.

01:15:08.720 --> 01:15:11.360
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, how do you get there from here?

01:15:11.360 --> 01:15:15.200
[Amit Varma]: And there is a massive transaction cost, if I might misuse that term,

01:15:15.200 --> 01:15:16.880
[Amit Varma]: and the poor kind of bear it.

01:15:16.880 --> 01:15:20.720
[Amit Varma]: So the best way to do it is in gradual steps and let the states

